1
00:01:25,960 --> 00:01:28,754
I owe everything to George Bailey.

2
00:01:29,171 --> 00:01:31,048
Help him, dear Father.

3
00:01:31,424 --> 00:01:34,468
Joseph, Jesus and Mary,

4
00:01:34,552 --> 00:01:37,179
help my friend Mr. Bailey.

5
00:01:37,638 --> 00:01:40,266
Help my son George tonight.

6
00:01:41,100 --> 00:01:42,977
He never thinks about himself, God.

7
00:01:43,060 --> 00:01:44,812
That's why he's in trouble.

8
00:01:44,895 --> 00:01:46,022
George is a good guy.

9
00:01:47,231 --> 00:01:48,482
Give him a break, God.

10
00:01:48,566 --> 00:01:50,693
I love him, dear Lord.

11
00:01:50,776 --> 00:01:52,653
Watch over him tonight.

12
00:01:53,112 --> 00:01:54,447
Please, God.

13
00:01:54,530 --> 00:01:56,824
Something's the matter with Daddy.

14
00:01:56,907 --> 00:01:59,201
Please bring Daddy back.

15
00:01:59,785 --> 00:02:01,329
Please bring Daddy home.

16
00:02:01,412 --> 00:02:03,623
Watch over him tonight.

17
00:02:03,998 --> 00:02:06,292
Please bring Daddy back.

18
00:02:10,171 --> 00:02:12,214
Hello, Joseph. Trouble?

19
00:02:12,298 --> 00:02:14,884
Looks like we'll have
to send someone down.

20
00:02:14,967 --> 00:02:18,054
A lot of people asking for help
for a man named George Bailey.

21
00:02:18,137 --> 00:02:19,680
George Bailey?

22
00:02:19,764 --> 00:02:22,224
Yes. Tonight's his crucial night.
You're right.

23
00:02:22,308 --> 00:02:25,186
We'll have to send someone down
immediately. Whose turn is it?

24
00:02:25,269 --> 00:02:27,605
That's why I came to see you, sir.

25
00:02:27,813 --> 00:02:30,274
It's that clockmaker's turn again.

26
00:02:30,358 --> 00:02:33,611
Oh, Clarence.
Hasn't got his wings yet, has he?

27
00:02:33,694 --> 00:02:35,571
We've passed him up right along.

28
00:02:35,655 --> 00:02:39,116
Because, you know, sir,
he's got the IQ of a rabbit.

29
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:42,662
Yes, but he's got
the faith of a child. Simple.

30
00:02:42,745 --> 00:02:44,789
Joseph, send for Clarence.

31
00:02:48,084 --> 00:02:49,460
You sent for me, sir?

32
00:02:49,543 --> 00:02:52,588
Yes, Clarence.
A man down on Earth needs our help.

33
00:02:52,672 --> 00:02:54,256
Splendid. Is he sick?

34
00:02:54,340 --> 00:02:56,550
No, worse. He's discouraged.

35
00:02:56,634 --> 00:02:59,220
At exactly 10:45 p.m. Earth time,

36
00:02:59,303 --> 00:03:01,347
that man will be thinking seriously

37
00:03:01,430 --> 00:03:03,391
of throwing away God's greatest gift.

38
00:03:03,474 --> 00:03:07,061
Oh, dear, dear, his life?
Then I've only an hour to dress.

39
00:03:07,144 --> 00:03:08,396
What are they wearing now?

40
00:03:08,479 --> 00:03:11,607
You will spend that hour
getting acquainted with George Bailey.

41
00:03:11,691 --> 00:03:14,694
Sir, if I should
accomplish this mission,

42
00:03:14,777 --> 00:03:18,239
I mean, might I perhaps win my wings?

43
00:03:18,322 --> 00:03:20,741
I've been waiting
for over 200 years now, sir,

44
00:03:20,825 --> 00:03:22,410
and people are beginning to talk.

45
00:03:22,493 --> 00:03:23,953
What's that book you've got there?

46
00:03:24,036 --> 00:03:26,205
The Adventures of Tom Sawyer.

47
00:03:26,288 --> 00:03:28,666
Clarence, you do a good job
with George Bailey

48
00:03:28,749 --> 00:03:30,084
and you'll get your wings.

49
00:03:30,167 --> 00:03:31,919
Oh, thank you, sir. Thank you.

50
00:03:32,002 --> 00:03:34,755
Poor George. Sit down.

51
00:03:34,839 --> 00:03:35,965
Sit down? What are we...

52
00:03:36,048 --> 00:03:37,758
If you're going to help a man,

53
00:03:37,842 --> 00:03:40,177
you want to know something about him,
don't you?

54
00:03:40,261 --> 00:03:41,762
Well, naturally, of course. I...

55
00:03:41,846 --> 00:03:43,139
Now, keep your eyes open.

56
00:03:44,014 --> 00:03:45,099
See the town?

57
00:03:45,182 --> 00:03:47,893
Where? I don't see a thing.

58
00:03:47,977 --> 00:03:50,813
Oh, I forgot.
You haven't got your wings yet.

59
00:03:50,896 --> 00:03:53,858
Now, look, I'll help you out.
Concentrate.

60
00:03:54,567 --> 00:03:56,318
Begin to see something?

61
00:03:56,402 --> 00:03:59,113
Why, yes. This is amazing.

62
00:03:59,196 --> 00:04:01,782
If you ever get your wings,
you'll see all by yourself.

63
00:04:01,866 --> 00:04:03,617
Oh, wonderful.

64
00:04:03,701 --> 00:04:06,412
Yay! Yippee!

65
00:04:06,495 --> 00:04:08,456
Okay, boys, let's go.

66
00:04:08,539 --> 00:04:10,249
Hey, who's that?

67
00:04:10,332 --> 00:04:12,168
That's your problem. George Bailey.

68
00:04:12,251 --> 00:04:13,294
A boy?

69
00:04:13,377 --> 00:04:16,464
That's him when he was 12
back in 1919.

70
00:04:16,547 --> 00:04:19,884
Something happens here
you'll have to remember later on.

71
00:04:20,593 --> 00:04:22,303
Come on, Marty.

72
00:04:22,386 --> 00:04:24,263
Let's go, Marty!

73
00:04:25,055 --> 00:04:26,557
Attaboy, Marty.

74
00:04:27,475 --> 00:04:29,101
Hee-haw!

75
00:04:29,185 --> 00:04:31,145
Let's go, Sam. Hee-haw, Sammy!

76
00:04:31,896 --> 00:04:36,317
Here comes the scare-baby,
my kid brother Harry Bailey.

77
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:38,152
I'm not scared.

78
00:04:39,236 --> 00:04:40,654
Come on, Harry.

79
00:04:41,071 --> 00:04:42,698
Let's go, Harry!

80
00:04:42,782 --> 00:04:44,116
Come on, Harry!

81
00:04:44,200 --> 00:04:45,326
Come on, Harry!

82
00:04:45,409 --> 00:04:47,453
- Come on, Harry!
- Come on, Harry!

83
00:04:48,120 --> 00:04:49,538
Help, George, help!

84
00:04:49,622 --> 00:04:50,748
Help!

85
00:04:51,832 --> 00:04:54,335
Don't worry, Harry. I'm coming!

86
00:04:54,460 --> 00:04:56,712
- Help!
- Hang on, Harry!

87
00:04:56,879 --> 00:04:59,256
- Help.
- Make a chain, gang.

88
00:04:59,340 --> 00:05:01,842
George saved
his brother's life that day,

89
00:05:02,259 --> 00:05:05,596
but he caught a bad cold
which infected his left ear.

90
00:05:06,096 --> 00:05:08,265
Cost him his hearing in that ear.

91
00:05:08,349 --> 00:05:10,643
It was weeks
before he was able to go back

92
00:05:10,726 --> 00:05:14,104
to his after-school job
at old man Gower's drugstore.

93
00:05:14,855 --> 00:05:15,981
Mr. Potter.

94
00:05:16,065 --> 00:05:18,359
Who's that, a king?

95
00:05:18,442 --> 00:05:20,361
That's Henry F. Potter,

96
00:05:20,444 --> 00:05:23,781
the richest and meanest man
in the county.

97
00:05:27,993 --> 00:05:30,287
- Hee-haw! Hee-haw!
- Hee-haw! Hee-haw!

98
00:05:31,038 --> 00:05:32,289
Go to work, slave.

99
00:05:33,791 --> 00:05:35,960
Don't worry, we'll take care of it.

100
00:05:37,378 --> 00:05:39,380
Wish I had a million dollars.

101
00:05:40,005 --> 00:05:41,257
Hot dog!

102
00:05:45,135 --> 00:05:47,012
It's me, Mr. Gower. George Bailey.

103
00:05:47,096 --> 00:05:48,097
You're late.

104
00:05:48,180 --> 00:05:49,473
Yes, sir.

105
00:05:57,731 --> 00:05:59,149
Hello, George.

106
00:05:59,483 --> 00:06:00,776
Hello, Mary.

107
00:06:01,318 --> 00:06:02,403
Hello, Violet.

108
00:06:02,486 --> 00:06:04,071
Two cents' worth of shoelaces?

109
00:06:04,154 --> 00:06:05,531
She was here first.

110
00:06:05,614 --> 00:06:07,449
I'm still thinking.

111
00:06:07,533 --> 00:06:08,576
Shoelaces?

112
00:06:08,659 --> 00:06:10,286
Please, Georgie.

113
00:06:10,786 --> 00:06:11,912
I like him.

114
00:06:11,996 --> 00:06:13,747
You like every boy.

115
00:06:13,831 --> 00:06:15,499
What's wrong with that?

116
00:06:15,583 --> 00:06:17,084
Here you are.

117
00:06:18,043 --> 00:06:19,086
Help me down?

118
00:06:19,169 --> 00:06:21,088
Help you down?

119
00:06:27,803 --> 00:06:29,597
Made up your mind yet?

120
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:31,473
I'll take chocolate.

121
00:06:31,599 --> 00:06:34,268
- With coconuts?
- I don't like coconuts.

122
00:06:34,602 --> 00:06:36,312
You don't like coconuts?

123
00:06:36,604 --> 00:06:39,815
Say, brainless, don't you know
where coconuts come from?

124
00:06:40,441 --> 00:06:41,817
Lookit here.

125
00:06:41,901 --> 00:06:45,112
From Tahiti, the Fiji islands,
the Coral Sea.

126
00:06:45,404 --> 00:06:48,657
A new magazine. I never saw it before.

127
00:06:48,741 --> 00:06:51,368
Of course you never.
Only us explorers can get it.

128
00:06:51,869 --> 00:06:55,831
I've been nominated for membership
in the National Geographic Society.

129
00:06:57,207 --> 00:06:59,251
Is this the ear you can't hear on?

130
00:06:59,335 --> 00:07:02,922
George Bailey,
I'll love you till the day I die.

131
00:07:03,005 --> 00:07:06,008
I'm going out exploring someday.
You watch.

132
00:07:06,091 --> 00:07:09,345
And I'm gonna have a couple of harems
and maybe three or four wives.

133
00:07:09,428 --> 00:07:10,679
Wait and see.

134
00:07:13,599 --> 00:07:17,061
- George. George!
- Yes, sir?

135
00:07:17,144 --> 00:07:19,605
You're not paid to be a canary.

136
00:07:19,897 --> 00:07:21,231
No, sir.

137
00:07:48,592 --> 00:07:51,595
Mr. Gower, do you want something?
Anything?

138
00:07:51,762 --> 00:07:52,805
No.

139
00:07:53,472 --> 00:07:56,141
- Anything I can do back here?
- No.

140
00:07:56,600 --> 00:07:58,060
I'll get them, sir.

141
00:07:58,143 --> 00:08:00,938
Quick, take those capsules
over to Mrs. Blaine.

142
00:08:02,064 --> 00:08:03,357
She's waiting for them.

143
00:08:03,440 --> 00:08:04,775
Yes, sir.

144
00:08:27,381 --> 00:08:29,466
They have the diphtheria there,
haven't they, sir?

145
00:08:29,550 --> 00:08:30,634
Yeah.

146
00:08:30,968 --> 00:08:32,469
Is it a charge, sir?

147
00:08:32,761 --> 00:08:34,138
Yes, George.

148
00:08:34,722 --> 00:08:35,848
Mr. Gower, ll...

149
00:08:35,931 --> 00:08:38,350
- Oh, get going.
- Yes, sir.

150
00:09:05,044 --> 00:09:07,046
Avast there, Captain Cook.
Where you heading?

151
00:09:07,129 --> 00:09:09,590
- I've got to see Pop, Uncle Billy.
- Some other time, George.

152
00:09:09,673 --> 00:09:11,425
- It's important.
- There's a squall in there.

153
00:09:11,508 --> 00:09:13,052
It's shaping up into a storm.

154
00:09:13,135 --> 00:09:15,262
- Uncle Billy, telephone.
- Who is it?

155
00:09:15,345 --> 00:09:17,598
- Bank examiner.
- Bank examiner?

156
00:09:18,182 --> 00:09:19,892
I should have called him yesterday.

157
00:09:19,975 --> 00:09:21,602
Switch it inside.

158
00:09:23,854 --> 00:09:25,272
I'm not crying, Mr. Potter.

159
00:09:25,355 --> 00:09:27,232
Well, you're begging.
That's a whole lot worse.

160
00:09:27,316 --> 00:09:29,109
All I'm asking for is 30 days more.

161
00:09:29,193 --> 00:09:30,444
- Pop.
- Just a minute, Son.

162
00:09:30,527 --> 00:09:33,238
Just 30 short days.
I'll dig up that $5,000 somehow.

163
00:09:33,405 --> 00:09:34,740
- Shove me up, shove me up.
- Pop.

164
00:09:34,823 --> 00:09:36,617
- Just a minute.
- Have you put any real pressure

165
00:09:36,700 --> 00:09:39,161
on these people of yours
to pay those mortgages?

166
00:09:39,244 --> 00:09:41,580
Times are bad, Mr. Potter.
A lot of these people are out of work.

167
00:09:41,663 --> 00:09:42,748
Well, then, foreclose.

168
00:09:42,831 --> 00:09:44,458
I can't do that.
These families have children.

169
00:09:44,541 --> 00:09:46,126
- Pop.
- They're not my children.

170
00:09:46,210 --> 00:09:48,128
But they're somebody's children,
Mr. Potter.

171
00:09:48,212 --> 00:09:50,756
Are you running a business
or a charity ward?

172
00:09:50,839 --> 00:09:52,966
- Well, all right...
- Not with my money.

173
00:09:53,050 --> 00:09:55,636
Mr. Potter, what makes you
such a hard-skulled character?

174
00:09:55,719 --> 00:09:57,554
You have no family, no children.

175
00:09:57,638 --> 00:09:59,473
You can't begin
to spend all the money you've got.

176
00:09:59,556 --> 00:10:02,810
I suppose I should give it
to miserable failures

177
00:10:02,893 --> 00:10:06,146
like you and that idiot brother
of yours to spend for me.

178
00:10:06,230 --> 00:10:07,439
He's not a failure!

179
00:10:07,523 --> 00:10:10,317
- You can't say that about my father.
- George, George. Quiet, George.

180
00:10:10,400 --> 00:10:11,777
You're not.
You're the biggest man in town...

181
00:10:11,860 --> 00:10:13,362
- Run along, run along.
- ...bigger than him,

182
00:10:13,445 --> 00:10:15,614
- bigger than everybody.
- Gives you an idea of the Baileys.

183
00:10:15,697 --> 00:10:17,449
Don't let him say that about you, Pop.

184
00:10:17,533 --> 00:10:19,159
All right, Son. All right. Thanks.

185
00:10:19,243 --> 00:10:20,994
I'll talk to you tonight.

186
00:10:28,001 --> 00:10:29,378
What?

187
00:10:29,461 --> 00:10:32,798
Why, that medicine should have
been there an hour ago.

188
00:10:33,298 --> 00:10:35,843
It will be over in five minutes,
Mrs. Blaine.

189
00:10:39,763 --> 00:10:42,015
Where's Mrs. Blaine's box of capsules?

190
00:10:42,099 --> 00:10:43,767
I... You...

191
00:10:44,560 --> 00:10:45,936
Didn't you hear what I said?

192
00:10:46,019 --> 00:10:47,104
Yes, sir...

193
00:10:47,187 --> 00:10:49,690
What kind of tricks
are you playing anyway?

194
00:10:51,775 --> 00:10:54,444
Why didn't you deliver them
right away?

195
00:10:54,528 --> 00:10:56,029
Don't you know that boy's very sick?

196
00:10:56,113 --> 00:10:57,614
You're hurting my sore ear.

197
00:10:57,698 --> 00:10:59,283
You lazy loafer.

198
00:10:59,366 --> 00:11:01,285
Mr. Gower,
you don't know what you're doing.

199
00:11:01,368 --> 00:11:03,245
You put something wrong
in those capsules.

200
00:11:03,328 --> 00:11:04,580
I know you're unhappy.

201
00:11:04,663 --> 00:11:06,373
You got the telegram,
and you're upset.

202
00:11:06,456 --> 00:11:08,292
You put something bad
in those capsules.

203
00:11:08,375 --> 00:11:10,711
It wasn't your fault, Mr. Gower.

204
00:11:11,295 --> 00:11:13,172
Just look and see what you did.

205
00:11:13,255 --> 00:11:15,841
The bottle you took the powder from,
it's poison.

206
00:11:15,924 --> 00:11:17,634
I tell you, it's poison.

207
00:11:17,801 --> 00:11:19,553
I know you feel bad.

208
00:11:24,641 --> 00:11:26,643
- Oh!
- Don't hurt my sore ear again!

209
00:11:26,727 --> 00:11:30,772
- Don't hurt my sore ear again.
- Oh, no, no. Oh, George, George.

210
00:11:30,856 --> 00:11:33,692
Oh, Mr. Gower,
I won't ever tell anyone.

211
00:11:33,775 --> 00:11:35,152
I know how you're feeling.

212
00:11:35,235 --> 00:11:37,905
I won't ever tell a soul.
Hope to die, I won't.

213
00:11:37,988 --> 00:11:39,740
Oh, George. George.

214
00:11:40,199 --> 00:11:42,784
An overnight bag.
Genuine English cowhide.

215
00:11:42,868 --> 00:11:44,036
Combination lock.

216
00:11:44,119 --> 00:11:47,414
- Fitted up with brushes, combs...
- Nope, nope, nope, nope.

217
00:11:47,497 --> 00:11:49,541
Now, look, Joe. Now, look.

218
00:11:50,042 --> 00:11:52,169
I want a big one.

219
00:11:52,753 --> 00:11:54,004
What did you stop it for?

220
00:11:54,087 --> 00:11:57,341
I want you to take a good look
at that face.

221
00:11:57,424 --> 00:11:58,467
Who is it?

222
00:11:58,550 --> 00:11:59,593
George Bailey.

223
00:11:59,676 --> 00:12:02,679
Oh, you mean the kid that had his ears
slapped back by the druggist?

224
00:12:02,763 --> 00:12:04,056
That's the kid.

225
00:12:06,183 --> 00:12:08,143
It's a good face. I like it.

226
00:12:08,227 --> 00:12:10,020
! like George Bailey.

227
00:12:10,520 --> 00:12:13,148
Tell me, did he ever tell anyone
about the pills?

228
00:12:13,232 --> 00:12:14,399
Not a soul.

229
00:12:14,691 --> 00:12:17,486
Did he ever marry the girl?
Did he ever go exploring?

230
00:12:17,569 --> 00:12:19,321
Well wait and see.

231
00:12:19,988 --> 00:12:22,157
Big, see?
I don't want one for one night.

232
00:12:22,241 --> 00:12:24,243
I want something for 1,001 nights

233
00:12:24,326 --> 00:12:28,789
with plenty of room here for labels
from Italy and Baghdad, Samarkand.

234
00:12:28,872 --> 00:12:30,040
Great big thing, about...

235
00:12:30,123 --> 00:12:32,292
- I see. A flying carpet, huh?
- Yeah.

236
00:12:32,376 --> 00:12:34,795
I don't suppose you'd like
this old secondhand job, would you?

237
00:12:34,878 --> 00:12:36,088
Now you're talking.

238
00:12:36,171 --> 00:12:39,049
Gee whiz, I could use that as a raft
in case the boat sunk.

239
00:12:39,132 --> 00:12:41,385
- How much this cost?
- No charge.

240
00:12:42,052 --> 00:12:44,137
That's my trick ear, Joe.
It sounded like you said "no charge."

241
00:12:44,221 --> 00:12:45,222
That's right.

242
00:12:46,556 --> 00:12:48,141
Well, what's my name doing on it?

243
00:12:48,225 --> 00:12:51,270
A little present from old man Gower.
Came down and picked it out himself.

244
00:12:51,353 --> 00:12:54,731
He did? What do you know about that?
My old boss. Isn't that nice?

245
00:12:54,815 --> 00:12:56,066
What boat are you sailing on?

246
00:12:56,149 --> 00:12:57,651
I'm working across on a cattle boat.

247
00:12:57,734 --> 00:12:59,903
- A cattle boat?
- Okay, I like cows.

248
00:13:02,197 --> 00:13:04,157
Hello, Mr. Gower. How are you?

249
00:13:04,241 --> 00:13:06,660
Thanks ever so much for the baggage.
It's just exactly what I wanted.

250
00:13:06,743 --> 00:13:07,828
Forget it.

251
00:13:07,911 --> 00:13:10,497
- It's wonderful of you to think of me.
- Hope you enjoy it.

252
00:13:10,580 --> 00:13:12,374
<i>1 wish I had a million dollars.</i>

253
00:13:12,457 --> 00:13:13,709
Hot dog!

254
00:13:14,418 --> 00:13:16,044
Avast there, Captain Cook!

255
00:13:16,128 --> 00:13:18,338
- You got your sea legs yet?
- Parlez-vous francais, mister?

256
00:13:18,422 --> 00:13:20,716
Hey, send us some of those
picture postcards, will you, George?

257
00:13:20,799 --> 00:13:22,551
Hey, George,
don't take any plug nickels.

258
00:13:22,634 --> 00:13:24,303
Hey, George, your suitcase is leaking.

259
00:13:24,386 --> 00:13:25,595
Hey, Ernie!

260
00:13:26,221 --> 00:13:28,140
- Hi, Ernie. Hi, Bert.
- Hiya, George.

261
00:13:28,223 --> 00:13:30,017
- George.
- Hey, I'm a rich tourist today.

262
00:13:30,100 --> 00:13:31,518
How about driving me home in style?

263
00:13:31,601 --> 00:13:33,312
- Hop in, Your Highness. Hop in.
- Yes, sir.

264
00:13:33,395 --> 00:13:36,273
And for the carriage trade,
I put on my hat.

265
00:13:38,442 --> 00:13:40,110
Good afternoon, Mr. Bailey.

266
00:13:40,193 --> 00:13:41,403
Hello, Violet.

267
00:13:41,486 --> 00:13:43,780
Hey, you look good.
That's some dress you got on there.

268
00:13:43,864 --> 00:13:45,365
This old thing?

269
00:13:45,449 --> 00:13:47,951
Why, I only wear it
when I don't care how I look.

270
00:14:03,467 --> 00:14:05,886
- How would you like to take...
- Yes.

271
00:14:07,304 --> 00:14:08,972
Want to come along, Bert?
We'll show you the town.

272
00:14:09,056 --> 00:14:10,140
No, thanks.

273
00:14:10,223 --> 00:14:13,477
I think I'll go home
and see what the wife's doing.

274
00:14:15,312 --> 00:14:16,646
Family man.

275
00:14:18,148 --> 00:14:20,901
George, Harry,
you're shaking the house down.

276
00:14:20,984 --> 00:14:22,069
Stop it.

277
00:14:22,152 --> 00:14:24,821
Let them alone.
I wish I was up there with them.

278
00:14:24,905 --> 00:14:27,866
But Harry will tear his dinner suit.
George!

279
00:14:27,949 --> 00:14:29,868
That's why
all children should be girls.

280
00:14:29,951 --> 00:14:32,162
Well, if they were all girls
there wouldn't be any...

281
00:14:32,245 --> 00:14:33,622
Oh, never mind.

282
00:14:33,872 --> 00:14:36,249
George, Harry,
come down to dinner this minute.

283
00:14:36,333 --> 00:14:37,376
Everything's getting cold,

284
00:14:37,459 --> 00:14:39,378
and you know how long
we've been waiting for you.

285
00:14:39,461 --> 00:14:41,171
- Okay, Ma.
- Okay, Ma.

286
00:14:42,506 --> 00:14:44,508
- Ta-da!
- Ta-da!

287
00:14:46,927 --> 00:14:49,638
- We got a present for you, Pop.
- There you are.

288
00:14:51,932 --> 00:14:53,517
Oh, you two idiots.

289
00:14:54,309 --> 00:14:55,519
George, sit down and have dinner.

290
00:14:55,602 --> 00:14:56,603
- Fine.
- I've eaten.

291
00:14:56,686 --> 00:14:58,355
Well, aren't you gonna finish dressing
for your graduating party?

292
00:14:58,438 --> 00:14:59,439
Look at you!

293
00:14:59,523 --> 00:15:00,941
I don't care. It's George's tux.

294
00:15:01,024 --> 00:15:02,859
Annie, my sweet,
have you got those pies?

295
00:15:02,943 --> 00:15:05,153
If you lay a hand on me,
I'll hit you with this broom!

296
00:15:05,237 --> 00:15:08,448
Annie, I'm in love with you.
There's a moon out tonight.

297
00:15:08,532 --> 00:15:12,494
Boy, oh boy, oh boy! My last meal
in the old Bailey boarding house.

298
00:15:12,577 --> 00:15:14,496
Oh, my lands, my blood pressure.

299
00:15:14,579 --> 00:15:16,915
Pop, can I have the car? I got to
take over a lot of plates and things.

300
00:15:16,998 --> 00:15:17,999
What plates?

301
00:15:18,083 --> 00:15:19,459
Mom, I'm chairman
of the Eats Committee.

302
00:15:19,543 --> 00:15:20,710
We only need a couple of dozen.

303
00:15:20,794 --> 00:15:24,172
Oh, no, you don't, Harry.
Now, not my best Haviland, no.

304
00:15:24,256 --> 00:15:26,258
Oh, let him have the plates, Mother.

305
00:15:26,341 --> 00:15:29,302
Hope you have a good trip, George.
Uncle Billy and I are gonna miss you.

306
00:15:29,386 --> 00:15:30,929
I'm gonna miss you, too, Pop.

307
00:15:31,138 --> 00:15:32,305
What's the matter? You look tired.

308
00:15:32,389 --> 00:15:34,641
I had another tussle
with Potter today.

309
00:15:34,891 --> 00:15:36,726
I thought when we put him
on the board of directors,

310
00:15:36,810 --> 00:15:38,145
he'd ease up on us a little bit.

311
00:15:38,478 --> 00:15:41,106
What's eating that old
money-grubbing buzzard anyway?

312
00:15:41,189 --> 00:15:44,109
He's a sick man, frustrated,
sick in his mind.

313
00:15:44,192 --> 00:15:45,986
Sick in his soul, if he has one.

314
00:15:46,069 --> 00:15:48,822
He hates everybody
that has anything that he can't have.

315
00:15:48,905 --> 00:15:50,615
He hates us mostly, I guess.

316
00:15:50,699 --> 00:15:52,033
Gangway. Gangway.

317
00:15:52,117 --> 00:15:53,577
- So long, Pop.
- So long.

318
00:15:53,660 --> 00:15:55,662
- You got a match?
- Very funny, very funny.

319
00:15:55,745 --> 00:15:56,746
Put those things in the car,

320
00:15:56,830 --> 00:15:58,999
and I'll get your tie and studs
ready for you. Now, hurry up.

321
00:15:59,082 --> 00:16:00,375
- Okay, Mom.
- Now, don't drop one of those.

322
00:16:00,459 --> 00:16:01,668
You coming later, George?

323
00:16:01,751 --> 00:16:03,003
What do you mean,
and be bored to death?

324
00:16:03,086 --> 00:16:04,713
Couldn't want a better death.
Lots of pretty girls,

325
00:16:04,796 --> 00:16:06,173
and we're gonna use
that new floor tonight, too.

326
00:16:06,256 --> 00:16:07,966
- I hope it works.
- No gin tonight, Son.

327
00:16:08,049 --> 00:16:09,259
Oh, Pop, just a little?

328
00:16:09,342 --> 00:16:11,178
No, Son. Not one drop.

329
00:16:11,595 --> 00:16:13,847
Boys and girls and music.

330
00:16:13,930 --> 00:16:15,849
Why do they need gin?

331
00:16:15,932 --> 00:16:18,977
Did I act like that
when I graduated from high school?

332
00:16:19,060 --> 00:16:20,228
Pretty much.

333
00:16:20,896 --> 00:16:23,356
You know, George, I wish we could send
Harry to college with you.

334
00:16:23,440 --> 00:16:26,067
Your mother and I talked it over
half the night.

335
00:16:26,151 --> 00:16:28,028
We have that all figured out.

336
00:16:28,111 --> 00:16:30,238
You see, Harry will take my job
at the Building and Loan,

337
00:16:30,322 --> 00:16:33,074
work there for four years,
then he'll go.

338
00:16:33,492 --> 00:16:34,826
Pretty young for that job.

339
00:16:34,910 --> 00:16:36,620
Well, no younger than I was.

340
00:16:36,703 --> 00:16:39,039
Well, you were born older, George.

341
00:16:40,081 --> 00:16:41,583
How's that?

342
00:16:41,666 --> 00:16:43,376
I said you were born older.

343
00:16:43,460 --> 00:16:44,836
I suppose you've decided
what you want to do

344
00:16:44,920 --> 00:16:46,213
when you get out of college.

345
00:16:46,505 --> 00:16:48,256
Well, you know
what I've always talked about,

346
00:16:48,340 --> 00:16:51,760
build things, design new buildings,
plan modern cities.

347
00:16:51,843 --> 00:16:53,178
All that stuff
I've been talking about.

348
00:16:53,261 --> 00:16:55,055
Still after that first million
before you're 307?

349
00:16:55,138 --> 00:16:57,599
I'll settle for half that in cash.

350
00:16:58,099 --> 00:17:00,310
Of course, it's just a hope.

351
00:17:01,311 --> 00:17:02,604
But you wouldn't consider coming back

352
00:17:02,687 --> 00:17:04,898
to the Building and Loan, would you?

353
00:17:06,483 --> 00:17:08,151
Well,... I...

354
00:17:10,820 --> 00:17:13,573
Annie, why don't you draw up a chair?
Then you'd be more comfortable,

355
00:17:13,657 --> 00:17:15,534
and you could hear everything
that's going on.

356
00:17:15,617 --> 00:17:18,078
I would if I thought
I'd hear anything worth listening to.

357
00:17:18,161 --> 00:17:19,704
You would, eh?

358
00:17:19,788 --> 00:17:21,998
I know it's soon to talk about it.

359
00:17:22,082 --> 00:17:24,668
No, now, Pop, I couldn't.

360
00:17:25,210 --> 00:17:27,671
I couldn't face being cooped up
for the rest of my life

361
00:17:27,754 --> 00:17:29,548
in a shabby little office.

362
00:17:31,174 --> 00:17:34,010
I'm sorry, Pop.
I didn't mean that, but I...

363
00:17:34,344 --> 00:17:36,721
It's this business
of nickels and dimes

364
00:17:36,805 --> 00:17:38,974
and spending all your life
trying to figure out

365
00:17:39,057 --> 00:17:40,976
how to save three cents
on a length of pipe.

366
00:17:41,059 --> 00:17:44,104
I'd go crazy. I want to do
something big and something important.

367
00:17:44,187 --> 00:17:47,148
You know, George,
I feel that, in a small way,

368
00:17:47,232 --> 00:17:49,150
we're doing something important,

369
00:17:49,234 --> 00:17:51,444
satisfying a fundamental urge.

370
00:17:51,528 --> 00:17:53,530
It's deep in the race
for a man to want his own roof

371
00:17:53,613 --> 00:17:55,824
and walls and fireplace.

372
00:17:55,907 --> 00:17:57,867
And we're helping him get those things

373
00:17:57,951 --> 00:17:59,619
in our shabby little office.

374
00:17:59,703 --> 00:18:03,373
I know, Pop. I know that.

375
00:18:03,748 --> 00:18:05,500
I wish I felt that...

376
00:18:06,626 --> 00:18:10,005
I've been hoarding pennies
like a miser here in order to...

377
00:18:10,380 --> 00:18:13,216
Most of my friends
have already finished college.

378
00:18:13,592 --> 00:18:16,720
I just feel like if I didn't get away,
I'd bust.

379
00:18:18,263 --> 00:18:21,433
Yes, yes, you're right, Son.

380
00:18:21,516 --> 00:18:23,226
You see what I mean, don't you, Pop?

381
00:18:23,310 --> 00:18:24,853
This town is no place for any man

382
00:18:24,936 --> 00:18:27,230
unless he's willing
to crawl to Potter.

383
00:18:27,314 --> 00:18:29,858
Now, you've got talent, Son.
I've seen it.

384
00:18:30,609 --> 00:18:33,820
You get yourself an education
and get out of here.

385
00:18:36,323 --> 00:18:38,199
Pop, you want a shock?

386
00:18:39,743 --> 00:18:41,828
I think you're a great guy.

387
00:18:45,290 --> 00:18:47,542
- Why, did you hear that, Annie?
- I heard it.

388
00:18:47,626 --> 00:18:50,003
It's about time
one of you lunkheads said it.

389
00:18:52,088 --> 00:18:53,923
I'm gonna miss old Annie.

390
00:18:57,385 --> 00:19:00,555
Pop, I think I'll get dressed
and go over to Harry's party.

391
00:19:00,639 --> 00:19:02,265
Have a good time, Son.

392
00:19:07,312 --> 00:19:08,438
Excuse me.

393
00:19:09,022 --> 00:19:10,065
There you are.

394
00:19:10,148 --> 00:19:11,232
George, hello.

395
00:19:11,316 --> 00:19:12,525
You know my kid brother George.

396
00:19:12,609 --> 00:19:14,569
- I'm gonna put him through college.
- Hello, George.

397
00:19:14,653 --> 00:19:15,945
Hee-haw!

398
00:19:16,029 --> 00:19:17,405
Sam Wainwright.

399
00:19:17,489 --> 00:19:19,032
How are you? When did you get here?

400
00:19:19,115 --> 00:19:21,201
This afternoon.
I thought I'd give the kids a treat.

401
00:19:21,284 --> 00:19:22,702
Old college graduate now.

402
00:19:22,786 --> 00:19:24,871
Yeah, old "Joe College" Wainwright
they call me.

403
00:19:24,954 --> 00:19:27,749
Well, freshman, looks like
you're gonna make it after all, huh?

404
00:19:27,832 --> 00:19:30,210
- Harry, you're the guy I want to see.
- Hello, Sam.

405
00:19:30,293 --> 00:19:32,379
- Coach has heard all about you.
- He has?

406
00:19:32,462 --> 00:19:34,297
Yeah, he's followed every game,
and his mouth's watering.

407
00:19:34,381 --> 00:19:36,549
He wants me to find out
if you're gonna come along with us.

408
00:19:36,633 --> 00:19:38,176
Well, I got to make some dough first.

409
00:19:38,259 --> 00:19:40,804
Well, you better make it fast.
We need great ends like you.

410
00:19:40,887 --> 00:19:42,555
Not broken down old guys
like this one.

411
00:19:42,639 --> 00:19:43,765
Hee-haw!

412
00:19:44,182 --> 00:19:46,226
George, welcome back.

413
00:19:46,309 --> 00:19:47,936
Hello, Mr. Partridge, how are you?

414
00:19:48,019 --> 00:19:50,230
Putting a pool under this floor
was a great idea.

415
00:19:50,313 --> 00:19:51,606
Saved us another building.

416
00:19:51,690 --> 00:19:53,566
Now, Harry, Sam, have a lot of fun.

417
00:19:53,650 --> 00:19:54,734
There's lots of stuff here
to eat and drink.

418
00:19:54,818 --> 00:19:56,903
- Lots of pretty girls around.
- Don't worry about the girls.

419
00:19:56,986 --> 00:19:58,405
A third dance... A third...

420
00:19:58,488 --> 00:20:01,574
- Hello, Violet.
- Hello. What am I bid?

421
00:20:01,658 --> 00:20:02,867
George.

422
00:20:02,951 --> 00:20:04,786
Marty! Well, it's old home week.

423
00:20:04,869 --> 00:20:06,913
- Marty!
- Sam, Harry, how are you?

424
00:20:06,996 --> 00:20:08,915
- Do me a favor, will you, George?
- What's that?

425
00:20:08,998 --> 00:20:11,418
- You remember my kid sister Mary.
- Oh, yeah. Yeah.

426
00:20:11,501 --> 00:20:13,753
"Mama wants you, Marty.
Mama wants you." Remember?

427
00:20:13,837 --> 00:20:15,213
Dance with her, will you?

428
00:20:15,296 --> 00:20:18,425
Oh, me? Well, I feel funny enough
already with all these kids.

429
00:20:18,508 --> 00:20:20,635
Come on, be a sport.
Just dance with her one time,

430
00:20:20,719 --> 00:20:22,929
and you'll give her
the thrill of her life. Hey, Sis!

431
00:20:23,012 --> 00:20:24,556
Don't be long, Marty.

432
00:20:24,639 --> 00:20:26,349
I'm not being a wet nurse to a...

433
00:20:26,433 --> 00:20:28,435
The next thing I knew,
some guy came up and tripped me.

434
00:20:28,518 --> 00:20:30,437
That's the reason
why I came in fourth.

435
00:20:30,520 --> 00:20:33,231
If it hadn't been for that,
that race'd have been a cinch.

436
00:20:33,314 --> 00:20:36,276
I tried to find out who it was later,
but I couldn't find out.

437
00:20:36,359 --> 00:20:40,029
Nobody'd ever tell you whoever it was,
because they'd be scared.

438
00:20:40,113 --> 00:20:41,573
"Cause they know
what kind of a guy I am.

439
00:20:41,656 --> 00:20:43,783
You remember George. This is Mary.

440
00:20:43,867 --> 00:20:45,493
Well, I'll be seeing you.

441
00:20:45,577 --> 00:20:46,619
Well, well, well.

442
00:20:46,703 --> 00:20:49,456
Now to get back to my story, see?

443
00:20:52,208 --> 00:20:53,918
Hey, this is my dance.

444
00:20:54,002 --> 00:20:55,587
Why don't you stop annoying people?

445
00:20:55,670 --> 00:20:57,797
Well, I'm sorry. Hey!

446
00:21:01,050 --> 00:21:03,636
- Well, hello.
- Hello.

447
00:21:04,137 --> 00:21:06,306
You look at me
as if you didn't know me.

448
00:21:06,389 --> 00:21:07,599
Well, I don't.

449
00:21:07,682 --> 00:21:09,976
You've passed me on the street
almost every day.

450
00:21:10,059 --> 00:21:11,144
Me?

451
00:21:11,227 --> 00:21:14,439
No. That was a little girl
named Mary Hatch. That wasn't you.

452
00:21:14,898 --> 00:21:18,276
Oh, yes! Oh, yes! Oh, yes!
The big Charleston contest!

453
00:21:20,487 --> 00:21:23,323
The prize, a genuine loving cup.

454
00:21:23,406 --> 00:21:26,117
Those not tapped by the judges
will remain on the floor.

455
00:21:26,201 --> 00:21:27,202
Let's go!

456
00:21:37,921 --> 00:21:39,172
I'm not very good at this.

457
00:21:39,255 --> 00:21:40,840
