Sir, my train, please.

499
00:25:19,851 --> 00:25:22,562
A pox upon me for a clumsy lout.

500
00:25:22,687 --> 00:25:25,898
Your caboose, milady.

501
00:25:26,816 --> 00:25:28,901
You may kiss my hand.

502
00:25:31,320 --> 00:25:32,822
Hey.

503
00:25:34,824 --> 00:25:36,159
Hey, Mary.

504
00:25:37,076 --> 00:25:40,246
As I was lumberin' down the street

505
00:25:40,329 --> 00:25:42,790
Down the street, down the street

506
00:25:43,041 --> 00:25:45,460
Okay, then. I'll throw a rock
at the old Granville house.

507
00:25:45,543 --> 00:25:47,712
Oh, no, don't. I love that old house.

508
00:25:47,795 --> 00:25:49,714
No, you see, you make a wish
and then try and break some glass.

509
00:25:49,797 --> 00:25:51,424
And you got to be
a pretty good shot nowadays, too.

510
00:25:51,507 --> 00:25:54,385
Oh, no, George, don't.
It's full of romance, that old place.

511
00:25:54,761 --> 00:25:56,679
I'd like to live in it.

512
00:25:56,846 --> 00:25:57,889
In that place?

513
00:25:57,972 --> 00:26:00,266
I wouldn't live in it as a ghost.
Now, watch.

514
00:26:00,349 --> 00:26:03,019
Right in the second floor, there. See?

515
00:26:07,732 --> 00:26:08,900
What did you wish, George?

516
00:26:08,983 --> 00:26:11,402
Not just one wish, a whole hatful.

517
00:26:11,569 --> 00:26:13,571
Mary, I know what
I'm gonna do tomorrow

518
00:26:13,654 --> 00:26:16,282
and the next day and next year
and the year after that.

519
00:26:16,365 --> 00:26:19,202
I'm shaking the dust of this
crummy little town off my feet,

520
00:26:19,285 --> 00:26:21,037
and I'm gonna see the world!

521
00:26:21,120 --> 00:26:24,207
Italy, Greece, the Parthenon,
the Coliseum.

522
00:26:24,290 --> 00:26:26,959
Then I'm coming back here and go
to college to see what they know.

523
00:26:27,043 --> 00:26:28,628
And then I'm gonna build things.

524
00:26:28,711 --> 00:26:30,129
I'm gonna build airfields.

525
00:26:30,213 --> 00:26:32,632
I'm gonna build skyscrapers
100 stories high.

526
00:26:32,715 --> 00:26:35,093
I'm gonna build bridges a mile long.

527
00:26:35,343 --> 00:26:36,385
What, are you gonna throw a rock?

528
00:26:41,682 --> 00:26:43,392
Hey, that's pretty good.

529
00:26:44,060 --> 00:26:46,062
What did you wish, Mary?

530
00:26:48,815 --> 00:26:51,025
Buffalo gals
can't you come out tonight?

531
00:26:51,109 --> 00:26:52,360
Can't you come out tonight?

532
00:26:52,443 --> 00:26:53,986
Can't you come out tonight?

533
00:26:54,070 --> 00:26:57,115
Buffalo gals
can't you come out tonight

534
00:26:57,198 --> 00:27:00,201
And

535
00:27:00,284 --> 00:27:04,330
Dance by the light of the moon?

536
00:27:04,413 --> 00:27:06,332
What did you wish
when you threw that rock?

537
00:27:06,415 --> 00:27:07,834
- Oh, no.
- Come on, tell me.

538
00:27:07,917 --> 00:27:09,710
If I told you, it might not come true.

539
00:27:09,794 --> 00:27:11,671
What is it you want, Mary?

540
00:27:11,754 --> 00:27:14,257
What do you want? You want the moon?

541
00:27:14,590 --> 00:27:16,717
Just say the word,
and I'll throw a lasso around it

542
00:27:16,801 --> 00:27:17,885
and pull it down.

543
00:27:17,969 --> 00:27:21,764
Hey, that's a pretty good idea.
I'll give you the moon, Mary.

544
00:27:21,931 --> 00:27:23,349
I'll take it.

545
00:27:23,766 --> 00:27:24,851
Then what?

546
00:27:25,309 --> 00:27:28,813
Well, then you could swallow it,
and it would all dissolve, see?

547
00:27:29,272 --> 00:27:32,692
And the moonbeams would shoot out
of your fingers and your toes

548
00:27:32,775 --> 00:27:34,777
and the ends of your hair.

549
00:27:36,112 --> 00:27:38,406
- Am I talking too much?
- Yes!

550
00:27:39,824 --> 00:27:42,160
Why don't you kiss her
instead of talking her to death?

551
00:27:42,243 --> 00:27:43,286
How's that?

552
00:27:43,369 --> 00:27:45,955
Why don't you kiss her
instead of talking her to death?

553
00:27:48,457 --> 00:27:50,042
You want me to kiss her, huh?

554
00:27:50,126 --> 00:27:53,546
Youth is wasted on the wrong people.

555
00:27:54,589 --> 00:27:57,967
Hey. Hey, hold on, hey, mister.
Come on back out here!

556
00:27:58,050 --> 00:28:00,428
I'll show you some kissing
that'll put hair back on your head.

557
00:28:00,511 --> 00:28:01,762
What are you...

558
00:28:09,645 --> 00:28:10,730
Mary?

559
00:28:21,866 --> 00:28:23,868
Okay, I give up. Where are you?

560
00:28:24,118 --> 00:28:27,079
Over here in the hydrangea bushes.

561
00:28:27,330 --> 00:28:29,665
Here you are. Catch.

562
00:28:30,833 --> 00:28:33,169
Wait a minute. What am I doing?

563
00:28:37,340 --> 00:28:39,884
This is a very interesting situation.

564
00:28:39,967 --> 00:28:41,802
Please give me my robe.

565
00:28:43,679 --> 00:28:46,390
A man doesn't get in a situation
like this every day.

566
00:28:46,474 --> 00:28:48,476
I'd like to have my robe.

567
00:28:48,559 --> 00:28:50,102
Not in Bedford Falls, anyway.

568
00:28:50,186 --> 00:28:52,396
- Ouch! Oh!
- Gesundheit.

569
00:28:53,356 --> 00:28:55,149
- George Bailey!
- This requires a little thought here.

570
00:28:55,233 --> 00:28:56,901
Give me my robe.

571
00:28:56,984 --> 00:28:59,403
I've read about things like this,
but I've never...

572
00:28:59,487 --> 00:29:02,615
Shame on you!
I'm gonna tell your mother on you.

573
00:29:02,698 --> 00:29:05,326
My mother's way up
on the corner there.

574
00:29:05,409 --> 00:29:07,370
I'll call the police.

575
00:29:07,453 --> 00:29:10,248
They're way downtown.
They'd be on my side, too.

576
00:29:10,331 --> 00:29:12,208
Then I'm going to scream!

577
00:29:12,875 --> 00:29:14,710
Maybe I could sell tickets.

578
00:29:15,503 --> 00:29:18,923
Let's see. No, the point is

579
00:29:19,006 --> 00:29:21,717
in order to get this robe...
I've got it.

580
00:29:22,009 --> 00:29:23,678
I'll make a deal with you, Mary.

581
00:29:23,761 --> 00:29:25,221
George! George!

582
00:29:28,557 --> 00:29:30,851
George, come on home! Quick!

583
00:29:30,935 --> 00:29:33,354
- Your father's had a stroke.
- What?

584
00:29:33,771 --> 00:29:35,273
Mary, Mary, I'm sorry. I've got to go.

585
00:29:35,356 --> 00:29:36,607
Come on, George, let's hurry.

586
00:29:36,691 --> 00:29:37,775
- Did you get a doctor?
- Yes.

587
00:29:37,858 --> 00:29:39,694
Campbell's there now.

588
00:29:50,288 --> 00:29:51,914
I think that's all
we'll need you for, George.

589
00:29:51,998 --> 00:29:53,165
I know you're anxious to make a train.

590
00:29:53,249 --> 00:29:54,834
I have a taxi waiting downstairs.

591
00:29:54,917 --> 00:29:57,753
I want the board to know
that George gave up his trip to Europe

592
00:29:57,837 --> 00:30:00,589
to help straighten things out here
these past few months.

593
00:30:00,673 --> 00:30:02,550
Good luck to you at school, George.

594
00:30:02,633 --> 00:30:04,593
- Good luck, George.
- Goodbye, George.

595
00:30:04,677 --> 00:30:07,305
And now we come to the real purpose
of this meeting,

596
00:30:07,388 --> 00:30:10,057
to appoint a successor
to our dear friend Peter Bailey.

597
00:30:10,141 --> 00:30:12,310
Mr. Chairman,
I'd like to get to my real purpose.

598
00:30:12,393 --> 00:30:14,603
- Wait just a minute now.
- Wait for what?

599
00:30:14,687 --> 00:30:18,024
I claim this institution
IS not necessary to this town.

600
00:30:18,107 --> 00:30:21,986
Therefore, Mr. Chairman, I make
a motion to dissolve this institution

601
00:30:22,069 --> 00:30:25,364
and turn its assets and liabilities
over to the receiver.

602
00:30:25,448 --> 00:30:27,366
Potter, you dirty, contemptible...
I'll wring his neck.

603
00:30:27,450 --> 00:30:28,492
George, did you hear
what that buzzard...

604
00:30:28,576 --> 00:30:29,618
Mr. Chairman.

605
00:30:29,702 --> 00:30:31,495
It's too soon after
Peter Bailey's death

606
00:30:31,579 --> 00:30:33,873
to talk about chloroforming
the Building and Loan.

607
00:30:33,956 --> 00:30:36,375
Peter Bailey died three months ago.

608
00:30:36,459 --> 00:30:38,294
I second Mr. Potter's motion.

609
00:30:38,377 --> 00:30:39,795
Very well. In that case,

610
00:30:39,879 --> 00:30:43,716
I'll ask the two executive officers
to withdraw. But before you go,

611
00:30:43,799 --> 00:30:46,969
I'm sure the whole board wishes
to express its deep sorrow

612
00:30:47,053 --> 00:30:49,221
- at the passing of Peter Bailey.
- Thank you very much.

613
00:30:49,305 --> 00:30:51,265
It was his faith and devotion

614
00:30:51,349 --> 00:30:52,892
that are responsible
for this organization.

615
00:30:52,975 --> 00:30:54,894
I'll go further than that.

616
00:30:54,977 --> 00:30:57,355
I'll say that to the public

617
00:30:57,438 --> 00:30:59,398
Peter Bailey
was the Building and Loan.

618
00:30:59,482 --> 00:31:01,734
That's fine, Potter, coming from you,

619
00:31:01,817 --> 00:31:03,778
considering that you probably
drove him to his grave.

620
00:31:03,861 --> 00:31:06,697
Peter Bailey was not a businessman.

621
00:31:06,781 --> 00:31:08,240
That's what killed him.

622
00:31:08,324 --> 00:31:11,035
Oh, I don't mean any disrespect
to him. God rest his soul.

623
00:31:11,118 --> 00:31:14,580
He was a man of high ideals,
so-called.

624
00:31:14,997 --> 00:31:18,918
But ideals without common sense
can ruin this town.

625
00:31:19,668 --> 00:31:22,505
Now, you take this loan here
to Ernie Bishop,

626
00:31:22,588 --> 00:31:25,925
you know,
that fellow that sits around all day

627
00:31:26,008 --> 00:31:28,761
on his brains in his taxi, you know.

628
00:31:28,844 --> 00:31:32,681
I happen to know
the bank turned down this loan.

629
00:31:32,765 --> 00:31:34,433
But he comes here,

630
00:31:34,517 --> 00:31:39,313
and we're building him
a house worth $5,000.

631
00:31:40,064 --> 00:31:42,483
- Why?
- Well, I handled that, Mr. Potter.

632
00:31:42,566 --> 00:31:45,444
You have all the papers there.
His salary, insurance.

633
00:31:45,528 --> 00:31:46,862
I can personally vouch
for his character.

634
00:31:46,946 --> 00:31:48,864
- A friend of yours?
- Yes, sir.

635
00:31:49,407 --> 00:31:53,202
You see, if you shoot pool
with some employee here,

636
00:31:53,285 --> 00:31:55,538
you can come and borrow money.

637
00:31:55,788 --> 00:31:57,706
What does that get us?

638
00:31:57,790 --> 00:32:00,668
A discontented, lazy rabble

639
00:32:00,751 --> 00:32:02,628
instead of a thrifty working class.

640
00:32:02,711 --> 00:32:06,549
And all because
a few starry-eyed dreamers

641
00:32:06,632 --> 00:32:09,802
like Peter Bailey stir them up
and fill their heads

642
00:32:09,885 --> 00:32:12,138
with a lot of impossible ideas.

643
00:32:12,221 --> 00:32:14,056
Now, I say...

644
00:32:14,140 --> 00:32:16,976
Just a minute. Just a minute.
Now, hold on, Mr. Potter.

645
00:32:17,059 --> 00:32:20,312
You're right when you say my father
was no businessman. I know that.

646
00:32:20,396 --> 00:32:23,065
Why he ever started this cheap
penny-ante Building and Loan

647
00:32:23,149 --> 00:32:24,233
I'll never know.

648
00:32:24,316 --> 00:32:25,568
But neither you nor anybody else

649
00:32:25,651 --> 00:32:27,153
can say anything
against his character,

650
00:32:27,236 --> 00:32:28,988
because his whole life was...

651
00:32:29,071 --> 00:32:31,657
Why, in the 25 years since he
and Uncle Billy started this thing,

652
00:32:31,740 --> 00:32:34,076
he never once thought of himself.
Isn't that right, Uncle Billy?

653
00:32:34,160 --> 00:32:36,996
He didn't save enough money
to send Harry to school, let alone me.

654
00:32:37,079 --> 00:32:39,832
But he did help a few people
get out of your slums, Mr. Potter.

655
00:32:39,915 --> 00:32:41,000
And what's wrong with that?

656
00:32:41,083 --> 00:32:44,003
Why, here,
you're all businessmen here.

657
00:32:44,086 --> 00:32:45,296
Don't it make them better citizens,

658
00:32:45,379 --> 00:32:47,339
and doesn't it make them
better customers?

659
00:32:47,423 --> 00:32:49,675
You said that they...
What'd you say just a minute ago?

660
00:32:49,758 --> 00:32:51,552
They had to wait and save their money

661
00:32:51,635 --> 00:32:53,095
before they even thought
of a decent home.

662
00:32:53,179 --> 00:32:54,847
Wait? Wait for what?

663
00:32:54,930 --> 00:32:56,640
Until their children grow up
and leave them?

664
00:32:56,724 --> 00:32:58,893
Until they're so old
and broken-down that they...

665
00:32:58,976 --> 00:33:01,604
Do you know how long it takes
a working man to save $5,0007?

666
00:33:01,687 --> 00:33:05,065
Just remember this, Mr. Potter,
that this rabble you're talking about,

667
00:33:05,149 --> 00:33:06,942
they do most of the working and paying

668
00:33:07,026 --> 00:33:09,069
and living and dying
in this community.

669
00:33:09,153 --> 00:33:11,614
Well, is it too much to have them work
and pay and live and die

670
00:33:11,697 --> 00:33:13,491
in a couple of decent rooms
and a bath?

671
00:33:13,574 --> 00:33:15,659
Anyway, my father didn't think so.

672
00:33:16,327 --> 00:33:18,621
People were human beings to him,
but to you,

673
00:33:18,704 --> 00:33:21,624
a warped, frustrated old man,
they're cattle.

674
00:33:21,790 --> 00:33:24,251
Well, in my book, he died
a much richer man than you'll ever be.

675
00:33:24,335 --> 00:33:26,212
I'm not interested in your book.

676
00:33:26,295 --> 00:33:28,631
I'm talking about
the Building and Loan.

677
00:33:28,714 --> 00:33:30,883
I know very well
what you're talking about.

678
00:33:30,966 --> 00:33:33,260
You're talking about something
you can't get your fingers on,

679
00:33:33,344 --> 00:33:36,180
and it's galling you. That's what
you're talking about, I know.

680
00:33:36,263 --> 00:33:38,557
Well, I've said too much. I...

681
00:33:38,974 --> 00:33:41,936
You're the Board here.
You do what you want with this thing.

682
00:33:42,019 --> 00:33:43,604
There's just one thing more, though.

683
00:33:43,687 --> 00:33:46,315
This town needs
this measly one-horse institution

684
00:33:46,398 --> 00:33:49,985
if only to have some place where people
can come without crawling to Potter.

685
00:33:50,069 --> 00:33:51,153
Come on, Uncle Billy.

686
00:33:57,243 --> 00:34:00,579
Sentimental hogwash. I want my motion.

687
00:34:02,706 --> 00:34:05,251
Boy, oh boy, that was telling him,
George, old boy.

688
00:34:05,334 --> 00:34:07,169
You shut his big mouth.
You should have heard him.

689
00:34:07,253 --> 00:34:08,921
What happened?
We heard a lot of yelling.

690
00:34:09,004 --> 00:34:11,674
Well, we're being voted
out of business after 25 years.

691
00:34:11,757 --> 00:34:15,261
- Easy come, easy go.
- Here it is. "Help wanted. Female."

692
00:34:15,344 --> 00:34:17,304
You still want me
to hang around, George?

693
00:34:17,388 --> 00:34:19,932
- Yeah, I'll be right down.
- Yeah, hey, you'll miss your train.

694
00:34:20,015 --> 00:34:21,809
You're a week late for school already.
Go on.

695
00:34:21,892 --> 00:34:24,687
- What's going on in there?
- Never mind. Don't worry about that.

696
00:34:24,770 --> 00:34:27,815
They're putting us out of business.
So what? I can get another job.

697
00:34:27,898 --> 00:34:29,608
- I'm only 55.
- 56.

698
00:34:29,692 --> 00:34:32,069
Go on, go on.
Hey, look, you gave up your boat trip,

699
00:34:32,152 --> 00:34:33,737
now you don't want to miss college,
too, do you?

700
00:34:33,821 --> 00:34:36,282
George! George!
They voted Potter down.

701
00:34:36,365 --> 00:34:38,158
They want to keep it going.

702
00:34:39,159 --> 00:34:40,703
You did it, George. You did it.

703
00:34:40,786 --> 00:34:42,955
They got one condition,
only one condition.

704
00:34:43,038 --> 00:34:44,623
- What's that?
- And that's the best part of it.

705
00:34:44,707 --> 00:34:46,750
They've appointed George here
as Executive Secretary

706
00:34:46,834 --> 00:34:48,127
to take his father's place.

707
00:34:48,210 --> 00:34:49,253
Oh, no! But, Uncle Billy...

708
00:34:49,336 --> 00:34:51,046
You can keep him on. That's all right.

709
00:34:51,130 --> 00:34:53,048
As Secretary,
you can hire anyone you like.

710
00:34:53,132 --> 00:34:55,759
Dr. Campbell, now let's get
this thing straight. I'm leaving.

711
00:34:55,843 --> 00:34:57,469
I'm leaving right now.
I'm going to school.

712
00:34:57,553 --> 00:35:00,014
This is my last chance.
Uncle Billy here, he's your man.

713
00:35:00,097 --> 00:35:02,933
But, George,
they'll vote with Potter otherwise.

714
00:35:04,768 --> 00:35:07,771
- I know, I know, he didn't go.
- That's right.

715
00:35:08,063 --> 00:35:09,106
Not only that,

716
00:35:09,189 --> 00:35:11,191
but he gave his school money
to his brother, Harry,

717
00:35:11,275 --> 00:35:12,776
and sent him to college.

718
00:35:12,860 --> 00:35:14,737
Harry became a football star.

719
00:35:14,820 --> 00:35:16,071
Made second team all-American.

720
00:35:16,530 --> 00:35:18,824
Yeah, but what happened to George?

721
00:35:18,907 --> 00:35:22,119
George got four years older,
waiting for Harry to come back

722
00:35:22,202 --> 00:35:24,288
and take over the Building and Loans.

723
00:35:24,371 --> 00:35:26,665
There are plenty of jobs around
for somebody that likes to travel.

724
00:35:26,749 --> 00:35:27,791
Look at this. Here.

725
00:35:27,875 --> 00:35:32,171
Venezuela oil fields. "Wanted,
man with construction experience."

726
00:35:32,254 --> 00:35:34,298
Here's the Yukon, right here.

727
00:35:34,381 --> 00:35:36,759
"Wanted,
man with engineering experience."

728
00:35:37,885 --> 00:35:39,678
There she blows.

729
00:35:39,762 --> 00:35:42,681
You know what the three most exciting
sounds in the world are?

730
00:35:42,765 --> 00:35:45,017
Breakfast is served.
Lunch is served. Dinner...

731
00:35:45,100 --> 00:35:48,812
No, no, no, no! Anchor chains,
plane motors and train whistles.

732
00:35:48,896 --> 00:35:51,023
- Peanut?
- There's the professor now.

733
00:35:51,106 --> 00:35:53,442
Old Professor Phi Beta Kappa
all-American Bailey.

734
00:35:53,525 --> 00:35:55,569
Why, old George
"Geographic Explorer" Bailey.

735
00:35:55,653 --> 00:35:56,737
What? No husky dogs? No sled?

736
00:35:56,820 --> 00:35:58,238
Uncle Billy,
you haven't changed a bit.

737
00:35:58,322 --> 00:35:59,865
Nobody ever changes here,
you know that.

738
00:35:59,948 --> 00:36:01,617
Oh, am I glad to see you.

739
00:36:01,700 --> 00:36:03,869
- Say, where's Mother?
