Would you tell that guy

981
00:49:31,968 --> 00:49:34,012
I'm giving him the chance
of a lifetime, do you hear?

982
00:49:34,095 --> 00:49:35,972
The chance of a lifetime!

983
00:49:39,267 --> 00:49:41,895
He says it's the chance of a lifetime.

984
00:49:45,398 --> 00:49:46,941
Now you listen to me.

985
00:49:47,150 --> 00:49:50,153
I don't want any plastics,
and I don't want any ground floors.

986
00:49:50,236 --> 00:49:52,197
And I don't want to get married,
ever, to anyone.

987
00:49:52,280 --> 00:49:53,698
You understand that?

988
00:49:53,781 --> 00:49:55,700
I want to do what I want to do.

989
00:49:55,783 --> 00:49:58,870
And you're... And you're...

990
00:49:58,953 --> 00:50:02,457
- Oh, Mary, Mary.
- George, George, George.

991
00:50:05,168 --> 00:50:06,461
Oh, Mary.

992
00:50:08,004 --> 00:50:11,591
Oh, dear. Oh, dear. Oh, dear.

993
00:50:13,218 --> 00:50:14,427
Mary...

994
00:50:15,512 --> 00:50:16,554
Here they come! Here they come!

995
00:50:42,288 --> 00:50:43,998
Goodbye, George!

996
00:50:47,168 --> 00:50:48,670
Goodbye!

997
00:50:56,135 --> 00:50:58,638
First Harry, now George.

998
00:50:58,721 --> 00:51:00,932
Annie, we're just two old maids now.

999
00:51:01,015 --> 00:51:03,142
You speak for yourself, Miss B.

1000
00:51:05,770 --> 00:51:09,190
If either of you two
see a stranger around here, it's me.

1001
00:51:11,359 --> 00:51:13,820
Hey, look.
There's somebody driving this cab.

1002
00:51:13,903 --> 00:51:15,738
Bert the cop sent this over.

1003
00:51:15,822 --> 00:51:18,199
He said to float away
to Happyland on the bubbles.

1004
00:51:18,283 --> 00:51:20,451
Oh, look at this. Old Bert. Champagne!

1005
00:51:20,535 --> 00:51:23,746
By the way, where are you two going
on this here now honeymoon?

1006
00:51:23,830 --> 00:51:25,957
Where are we going? Look at this.

1007
00:51:26,040 --> 00:51:28,418
There's the kitty, Ernie.
Here, come on, count it, Mary.

1008
00:51:28,501 --> 00:51:30,587
I feel like a bootlegger's wife. Look.

1009
00:51:30,670 --> 00:51:33,047
You know what we're gonna do?
We're gonna shoot the works.

1010
00:51:33,131 --> 00:51:35,383
A whole week in New York.
A whole week in Bermuda.

1011
00:51:35,466 --> 00:51:37,927
The highest hotels,
the oldest champagne,

1012
00:51:38,011 --> 00:51:42,515
the richest caviar, the hottest music
and the prettiest wife.

1013
00:51:42,599 --> 00:51:44,851
That does it! Then what?

1014
00:51:44,934 --> 00:51:47,937
- Then what, honey?
- After that, who cares?

1015
00:51:48,396 --> 00:51:50,398
That does it, come here. Come here.

1016
00:51:53,568 --> 00:51:55,111
Don't look now,
but there's something funny

1017
00:51:55,194 --> 00:51:57,405
going on over there
at the bank, George.

1018
00:51:57,488 --> 00:51:58,615
I've never really seen one,

1019
00:51:58,698 --> 00:52:01,534
but that's got all the earmarks
of being a run.

1020
00:52:09,042 --> 00:52:12,045
Hey, Ernie, if you got any money
in the bank, you better hurry.

1021
00:52:12,128 --> 00:52:13,880
George, let's not stop. Let's go!

1022
00:52:13,963 --> 00:52:15,465
Just a minute, dear.

1023
00:52:18,468 --> 00:52:22,055
- Please, let's not stop, George.
- I'll be back in a minute, Mary.

1024
00:52:38,613 --> 00:52:41,115
Well, hello, everybody.
Mrs. Thompson, how are you?

1025
00:52:41,199 --> 00:52:44,035
Charlie? What's the matter here,
can't you get in?

1026
00:53:01,344 --> 00:53:03,096
What is this, Uncle Billy? A holiday?

1027
00:53:03,888 --> 00:53:05,056
George.

1028
00:53:05,765 --> 00:53:09,769
Come on in, everybody.
That's right. Just come on in.

1029
00:53:09,977 --> 00:53:11,270
Look out, you.

1030
00:53:13,481 --> 00:53:15,066
Now, look, why don't you all sit down?

1031
00:53:15,149 --> 00:53:17,360
There are a lot of seats over there.

1032
00:53:18,319 --> 00:53:20,238
Just make yourselves at home.

1033
00:53:21,823 --> 00:53:24,242
George, can I see you a minute?

1034
00:53:24,826 --> 00:53:27,078
- Why didn't you call me?
- I just did, but they said you left.

1035
00:53:27,161 --> 00:53:28,746
This is a pickle, George.
This is a pickle.

1036
00:53:28,830 --> 00:53:30,373
All right, now, what happened?
How did it start?

1037
00:53:30,456 --> 00:53:31,457
How does a thing like this ever start?

1038
00:53:31,541 --> 00:53:32,542
All I know is
the bank called our loan.

1039
00:53:32,625 --> 00:53:33,835
- When?
- About an hour ago.

1040
00:53:33,918 --> 00:53:35,962
- I handed over all our cash.
- All of it?

1041
00:53:36,045 --> 00:53:37,630
Every cent of it, and still it was
less than we owe them.

1042
00:53:37,714 --> 00:53:39,507
Holy mackerel!

1043
00:53:39,590 --> 00:53:41,718
And then I got scared, George,
and closed the doors.

1044
00:53:41,801 --> 00:53:43,469
I... I...

1045
00:53:45,513 --> 00:53:47,265
The whole town's gone crazy.

1046
00:53:47,348 --> 00:53:48,683
Yeah, hello?

1047
00:53:48,850 --> 00:53:50,893
George, it's Potter.

1048
00:53:54,439 --> 00:53:55,523
Hello?

1049
00:53:55,606 --> 00:53:59,944
George, there is a rumor around town
that you've closed your doors.

1050
00:54:00,027 --> 00:54:01,529
Is that true?

1051
00:54:01,863 --> 00:54:04,115
Oh, well, I'm very glad to hear that.

1052
00:54:04,198 --> 00:54:07,577
George, are you all right?
Do you need any police?

1053
00:54:07,660 --> 00:54:09,036
Police? What for?

1054
00:54:09,245 --> 00:54:13,082
Well, mobs get pretty ugly
sometimes, you know.

1055
00:54:13,374 --> 00:54:17,879
George, I'm going all out
to help in this crisis.

1056
00:54:18,171 --> 00:54:23,134
I've just guaranteed the bank
sufficient funds to meet their needs.

1057
00:54:23,468 --> 00:54:26,554
They'll close up for a week
and then reopen.

1058
00:54:27,722 --> 00:54:29,515
He just took over the bank.

1059
00:54:29,766 --> 00:54:31,392
I may lose a fortune,

1060
00:54:31,476 --> 00:54:35,313
but I'm willing
to guarantee your people, too.

1061
00:54:35,396 --> 00:54:37,899
Just tell them
to bring their shares over here,

1062
00:54:37,982 --> 00:54:40,568
and I will pay 50 cents on the dollar.

1063
00:54:40,651 --> 00:54:42,779
You never miss a trick,
do you, Potter?

1064
00:54:42,862 --> 00:54:44,030
Well, you're gonna miss this one.

1065
00:54:44,113 --> 00:54:45,907
If you close your doors
before 6:00 p.m.,

1066
00:54:45,990 --> 00:54:47,825
you will never reopen.

1067
00:54:56,626 --> 00:54:58,085
George, was it a nice wedding?

1068
00:54:58,169 --> 00:55:00,171
Gosh, I wanted to be there.

1069
00:55:00,588 --> 00:55:01,631
Yeah.

1070
00:55:03,549 --> 00:55:05,426
You can take this one off now.

1071
00:55:14,310 --> 00:55:19,649
Now, just remember that this thing
isn't as black as it appeared.

1072
00:55:29,408 --> 00:55:31,244
I have some news for you, folks.

1073
00:55:31,327 --> 00:55:32,745
I was just talking to old man Potter,

1074
00:55:32,829 --> 00:55:34,455
and he's guaranteed cash payments
at the bank.

1075
00:55:34,539 --> 00:55:36,082
The bank's gonna reopen next week.

1076
00:55:36,165 --> 00:55:38,084
But, George, I got my money here.

1077
00:55:38,167 --> 00:55:39,752
Did he guarantee this place?

1078
00:55:39,836 --> 00:55:41,546
Well, no, Charlie.
I didn't even ask him.

1079
00:55:41,629 --> 00:55:42,880
We don't need Potter over here.

1080
00:55:42,964 --> 00:55:44,632
Then, I'll take mine now.

1081
00:55:45,091 --> 00:55:46,676
No, but you're...

1082
00:55:47,468 --> 00:55:49,554
You're thinking of this place
all wrong,

1083
00:55:49,637 --> 00:55:53,266
as if I had the money back in a safe.
The money's not here.

1084
00:55:53,349 --> 00:55:55,893
Well, your money's in Joe's house.
That's right next to yours.

1085
00:55:55,977 --> 00:55:58,229
And in the Kennedy house
and Mrs. Macklin's house

1086
00:55:58,312 --> 00:55:59,814
and 100 others.

1087
00:55:59,897 --> 00:56:01,482
Why, you're lending them
the money to build,

1088
00:56:01,566 --> 00:56:03,609
and then, they're gonna pay it back
to you as best they can.

1089
00:56:03,693 --> 00:56:05,361
Now, what are you gonna do,
foreclose on them?

1090
00:56:05,444 --> 00:56:11,492
I got $242 in here,
and $242 isn't going to break anybody.

1091
00:56:12,326 --> 00:56:14,954
Okay, Tom. All right.

1092
00:56:15,162 --> 00:56:17,748
Here you are. You sign this.
You'll get your money in 60 days.

1093
00:56:17,832 --> 00:56:19,000
Sixty days?

1094
00:56:19,083 --> 00:56:21,127
Now, that's what you agreed to
when you bought your shares.

1095
00:56:21,210 --> 00:56:23,337
- Tom! Tom, did you get your money?
- No.

1096
00:56:23,421 --> 00:56:24,422
Well, I did.

1097
00:56:24,505 --> 00:56:25,715
Old man Potter'll pay
50 cents on the dollar

1098
00:56:25,798 --> 00:56:27,174
for every share you've got.

1099
00:56:27,258 --> 00:56:29,844
- Fifty cents on the dollar!
- Yes, cash!

1100
00:56:29,927 --> 00:56:31,512
Well, what do you say?

1101
00:56:31,596 --> 00:56:34,223
Now, Tom, you have to stick
to your original agreement.

1102
00:56:34,307 --> 00:56:35,641
Now, give us 60 days on this.

1103
00:56:35,725 --> 00:56:37,768
- Okay, Randall.
- Are you going to go to Potter's?

1104
00:56:37,852 --> 00:56:39,979
Better to get half than nothing.

1105
00:56:40,062 --> 00:56:42,148
Tom! Tom!

1106
00:56:42,523 --> 00:56:44,358
Randall! Now, Randall, wait! Wait.

1107
00:56:44,775 --> 00:56:48,571
Now, listen. Now, listen to me.
I beg of you not to do this thing.

1108
00:56:48,654 --> 00:56:50,740
If Potter gets a hold
of this Building and Loan,

1109
00:56:50,823 --> 00:56:52,783
there'll never be another decent house
built in this town.

1110
00:56:52,867 --> 00:56:54,368
He's already got charge of the bank.

1111
00:56:54,452 --> 00:56:56,495
He's got the bus line.
He got the department stores.

1112
00:56:56,579 --> 00:56:59,290
And now he's after us. Why?
Well, it's very simple.

1113
00:56:59,373 --> 00:57:01,626
Because we're cutting in
on his business, that's why.

1114
00:57:01,709 --> 00:57:03,836
And because he wants
to keep you living in his slums

1115
00:57:03,920 --> 00:57:05,796
and paying the kind of rent
he decides.

1116
00:57:05,880 --> 00:57:07,840
Joe, you had one
of those Potter houses, didn't you?

1117
00:57:07,924 --> 00:57:08,925
Well, have you forgotten?

1118
00:57:09,008 --> 00:57:11,385
Have you forgotten what he charged you
for that broken-down shack?

1119
00:57:11,469 --> 00:57:14,597
Here, Ed, you know. You remember last
year when things weren't going so well

1120
00:57:14,680 --> 00:57:15,848
and you couldn't make your payments.

1121
00:57:15,932 --> 00:57:17,391
Well, you didn't lose your house,
did you?

1122
00:57:17,475 --> 00:57:19,226
You think Potter would've
let you keep it?

1123
00:57:19,310 --> 00:57:21,979
Can't you understand
what's happening here?

1124
00:57:22,063 --> 00:57:23,648
Don't you see what's happening?

1125
00:57:23,731 --> 00:57:26,484
Potter isn't selling.
Potter's buying, and why?

1126
00:57:26,567 --> 00:57:28,736
Because we're panicky and he's not.
That's why.

1127
00:57:28,819 --> 00:57:30,029
He's picking up some bargain.

1128
00:57:30,112 --> 00:57:32,490
Now we can get through
this thing all right.

1129
00:57:32,573 --> 00:57:34,367
We've got to stick together, though.

1130
00:57:34,450 --> 00:57:35,952
We've got to have faith in each other.

1131
00:57:36,035 --> 00:57:39,246
But my husband hasn't worked
in over a year, and I need money.

1132
00:57:39,330 --> 00:57:41,040
How am going to live
until the bank opens?

1133
00:57:41,123 --> 00:57:43,459
- I got doctor bills to pay.
- I need cash.

1134
00:57:43,542 --> 00:57:45,461
I can't feed my kids on faith.

1135
00:57:45,544 --> 00:57:47,213
How much do you need?

1136
00:57:47,296 --> 00:57:50,758
Hey! I got $2,000.

1137
00:57:51,425 --> 00:57:53,886
Here's $2,000. This'll tide us over
till the bank reopens.

1138
00:57:53,970 --> 00:57:56,764
- All right, Tom, how much do you need?
- $242.

1139
00:57:56,847 --> 00:57:59,350
Tom, just enough to tide you over
until the bank reopens.

1140
00:57:59,433 --> 00:58:01,644
I'll take $242.

1141
00:58:04,438 --> 00:58:06,190
- There you are.
- That'll close my account.

1142
00:58:06,273 --> 00:58:08,609
Your account's still here.
That's a loan.

1143
00:58:08,693 --> 00:58:12,029
- Okay. All right, Ed?
- I got $300 here, George.

1144
00:58:12,113 --> 00:58:15,700
Now, Ed, what'll it take
till the bank opens? What do you need?

1145
00:58:15,783 --> 00:58:18,160
Well, I suppose $20.

1146
00:58:18,244 --> 00:58:21,038
$20. Now you're talking.
Thanks, Ed. That's fine.

1147
00:58:21,122 --> 00:58:22,748
All right, now, Mrs. Thompson,
how much do you want?

1148
00:58:22,832 --> 00:58:24,125
But it's your own money, George.

1149
00:58:24,208 --> 00:58:25,876
Never mind about that.
How much do you want?

1150
00:58:25,960 --> 00:58:28,045
- I can get along with $20, all right.
- $20, fine.

1151
00:58:28,129 --> 00:58:30,297
- And I'll sign the paper.
- You don't have to sign anything.

1152
00:58:30,381 --> 00:58:32,508
I know you. You pay it when you can.
That's okay.

1153
00:58:32,591 --> 00:58:35,970
- All right, Mrs. Davis?
- Could I have $17.507?

1154
00:58:37,805 --> 00:58:41,225
Bless your heart. Of course
you can have it. You got 50 cents?

1155
00:58:41,308 --> 00:58:42,685
- Seven...
- We're gonna make it, George.

1156
00:58:42,768 --> 00:58:44,270
- ...SIX...
- They'll never close us up today!

1157
00:58:44,353 --> 00:58:48,858
...five, four, three, two,

1158
00:58:48,983 --> 00:58:51,068
one, bingo!

1159
00:58:51,152 --> 00:58:52,820
We made it! Close the door, Eustace!
We made it.

1160
00:58:52,903 --> 00:58:55,823
Look, look, we're still in business.
We've still got 2 bucks left.

1161
00:58:55,906 --> 00:58:57,742
Look, let's have some of that.
Let's celebrate!

1162
00:58:57,825 --> 00:58:59,243
Get some glasses, Tilly.

1163
00:58:59,326 --> 00:59:02,580
- Well, a couple of financial wizards.
- Call us Rockefellers.

1164
00:59:02,663 --> 00:59:05,166
Get a tray for these two
great big important simoleons here.

1165
00:59:05,249 --> 00:59:06,792
We'll save them for seed. A toast.

1166
00:59:06,876 --> 00:59:10,337
A toast. A toast to Mama Dollar
and to Papa Dollar,

1167
00:59:10,421 --> 00:59:12,548
and if you want to keep this old
Building and Loan in business,

1168
00:59:12,631 --> 00:59:14,091
you better have a family real quick.

1169
00:59:14,175 --> 00:59:17,011
- I wish they were rabbits.
- I wish they were, too.

1170
00:59:17,136 --> 00:59:20,181
Okay, let's put them in the safe
and see what happens.

1171
00:59:27,605 --> 00:59:28,773
Close the door.

1172
00:59:28,856 --> 00:59:30,775
Folks, folks, wedding cigars.

1173
00:59:30,858 --> 00:59:34,278
Wedding. Holy mackerel, I'm married.

1174
00:59:34,361 --> 00:59:36,989
Where's Mary? Mary! Poor...

1175
00:59:37,073 --> 00:59:39,241
Look, I got a train to catch.
Well, the train's gone.

1176
00:59:39,325 --> 00:59:41,702
I wonder if Ernie's still here
with his taxicab.

1177
00:59:41,786 --> 00:59:44,205
George, there's a call for you.

1178
00:59:44,288 --> 00:59:45,623
Look, will you get my wife
on the phone?

1179
00:59:45,706 --> 00:59:47,083
She's probably over at her mother's.

1180
00:59:47,166 --> 00:59:48,709
Mrs. Bailey is on the phone.

1181
00:59:48,793 --> 00:59:50,795
I don't want Mrs. Bailey.
I want my wife.

1182
00:59:50,878 --> 00:59:54,465
Mrs. Bailey! Oh, that's my wife.
Here, I'll take it in here.

1183
00:59:54,840 --> 00:59:57,885
Mary. Hello. Listen, dear, I'm sorry.

1184
00:59:58,344 --> 01:00:02,056
Huh? Come home? What home?

1185
01:00:02,807 --> 01:00:06,560
320 Sycamore? Well, what...
Whose home is that?

1186
01:00:07,394 --> 01:00:09,563
The Waldorf Hotel, huh?

1187
01:00:20,157 --> 01:00:23,202
Hey, this is the company's posters,
and the company won't like this.

1188
01:00:23,285 --> 01:00:25,287
How would you like
to get a ticket next week?

1189
01:00:25,371 --> 01:00:26,664
You got any romance in you?

1190
01:00:26,747 --> 01:00:29,333
- Sure, I had it, but I got rid of it.
- Liver pills.

1191
01:00:29,416 --> 01:00:31,961
Who wants to see liver pills
on their honeymoon?

1192
01:00:32,044 --> 01:00:34,463
What we want is romantic places,
beautiful places,

1193
01:00:34,547 --> 01:00:36,382
places George wants to go.

1194
01:00:37,716 --> 01:00:39,468
Hey, Bert. Here he comes.

1195
01:00:39,552 --> 01:00:40,803
Come on, we got to get this up.
He's coming.

1196
01:00:40,886 --> 01:00:42,763
- Who?
- The groom, idiot.

1197
01:00:42,847 --> 01:00:44,723
This is their honeymoon.
Come on. Get that ladder.

1198
01:00:44,807 --> 01:00:46,350
What are they, ducks?

1199
01:00:49,145 --> 01:00:51,397
- Get that ladder up here.
- All right, all right.

1200
01:00:51,480 --> 01:00:54,316
- Hurry up. Hurry up. Hurry up.
- I'm hurrying.

1201
01:01:03,367 --> 01:01:06,036
Hiya... Good evening, sir.

1202
01:02:31,413 --> 01:02:33,958
Welcome home, Mr. Bailey.

1203
01:02:38,212 --> 01:02:40,506
Well, I'll be...

1204
01:02:45,678 --> 01:02:48,389
Mary. Mary, where did you...

1205
01:03:09,243 --> 01:03:11,161
Oh, Mary.

1206
01:03:13,831 --> 01:03:17,084
Remember the night we broke
some windows in this old house?

1207
01:03:18,502 --> 01:03:20,546
This is what I wished for.

1208
01:03:24,300 --> 01:03:26,468
You're wonderful.

1209
01:03:29,388 --> 01:03:31,390
You're wonderful.

1210
01:03:50,451 --> 01:03:54,455
- Martini, you rented a new house?
- Rent?

1211
01:03:55,748 --> 01:03:58,208
- You hear what he say, Mr. Bailey?
- What's that?

1212
01:03:58,292 --> 01:03:59,960
I own the house.

1213
01:04:00,210 --> 01:04:03,547
Me, Giuseppe Martini,
I own my own house.

1214
01:04:03,630 --> 01:04:06,967
No more we live like a pigs
in this Potter's Field.

1215
01:04:07,092 --> 01:04:10,179
- Mary, Mary!
- Mary, come on, bring the baby.

1216
01:04:10,846 --> 01:04:12,639
This is like a dream.

1217
01:04:12,723 --> 01:04:15,809
- I'll take the kids in the car.
- Oh, thank you, Mr. Bailey. Thank you.

1218
01:04:15,893 --> 01:04:18,812
All right, kids, here.
Here, get in here.

1219
01:04:18,896 --> 01:04:21,065
Now, one at a time.
Get right up on the seat there.

1220
01:04:22,608 --> 01:04:23,776
Sit down, there.

1221
01:04:23,859 --> 01:04:26,278
Here, now, get the dog, now.
That's it.

1222
01:04:27,488 --> 01:04:29,698
- Goat, too.
- Everybody!

1223
01:04:29,990 --> 01:04:31,325
All in!

1224
01:04:33,535 --> 01:04:35,454
Bye-bye! Bye-bye!

1225
01:04:38,123 --> 01:04:39,249
All in?

1226
01:04:58,227 --> 01:05:00,687
Mr. and Mrs. Martini, welcome home.

1227
01:05:01,188 --> 01:05:03,732
Good old George,
he's always making a speech.

1228
01:05:04,775 --> 01:05:06,110
Hee-haw!

1229
01:05:06,318 --> 01:05:09,947
- Sam Wainwright.
- Oh, who cares.

1230
01:05:10,489 --> 01:05:13,659
Bread. That this house
may never know hunger.

1231
01:05:14,368 --> 01:05:17,746
Salt. That life
may always have flavor.

1232
01:05:18,163 --> 01:05:21,625
And wine. That joy and prosperity
may reign forever.

1233
01:05:21,708 --> 01:05:23,460
Enter the Martini castle.

1234
01:05:25,295 --> 01:05:27,756
Look, Mr. Potter,
it's no skin off my nose.

1235
01:05:27,840 --> 01:05:29,633
I'm just your little rent collector.

1236
01:05:29,716 --> 01:05:32,553
But you can't laugh off
this Bailey Park anymore.

1237
01:05:32,636 --> 01:05:33,762
Look at it.

1238
01:05:34,638 --> 01:05:36,640
Congressman Blatz is here
to see you, sir.

1239
01:05:36,723 --> 01:05:39,726
Oh, tell the Congressman to wait.
Go on.

1240
01:05:39,810 --> 01:05:42,604
Fifteen years ago, a half a dozen
houses stuck here and there.

1241
01:05:42,688 --> 01:05:44,940
There's the old cemetery, squirrels,
buttercups, daisies.

1242
01:05:45,023 --> 01:05:47,234
I used to hunt rabbits there myself.

1243
01:05:48,068 --> 01:05:49,403
Look at it today.

1244
01:05:49,570 --> 01:05:52,406
Dozens of the prettiest little homes
you ever saw,

1245
01:05:52,573 --> 01:05:55,784
90% owned by suckers
who used to pay rent to you.

1246
01:05:55,868 --> 01:05:59,163
Your Potter's Field, my dear
Mr. Employer, is becoming just that.

1247
01:05:59,246 --> 01:06:02,708
And are the local yokels making with
those David and Goliath wisecracks.

1248
01:06:02,791 --> 01:06:04,543
Oh, they are, are they?

1249
01:06:04,626 --> 01:06:07,546
Even though they know the Baileys
never made a dime out of it.

1250
01:06:07,629 --> 01:06:10,132
You know very well why.
The Baileys were all chumps.

1251
01:06:10,215 --> 01:06:12,176
Every one of these homes is worth

1252
01:06:12,259 --> 01:06:14,344
twice what it cost
the Building and Loan to build.

1253
01:06:14,428 --> 01:06:16,889
- If I were you, Mr. Potter...
- You are not me.

1254
01:06:16,972 --> 01:06:20,476
As I say, it's no skin off my nose,

1255
01:06:23,604 --> 01:06:25,522
but one of these days
this bright young man

1256
01:06:25,606 --> 01:06:28,275
is gonna be asking
George Bailey for a job.

1257
01:06:30,652 --> 01:06:33,780
The Bailey family has been
a boil on my neck long enough.

1258
01:06:33,864 --> 01:06:35,949
- Yes, sir?
- Come in here.

1259
01:06:36,283 --> 01:06:38,494
We just stopped in town
to take a look at the new factory,

1260
01:06:38,577 --> 01:06:40,537
and then we're gonna
drive on down to Florida.

1261
01:06:40,621 --> 01:06:42,289
Why don't you
have your friends join us?

1262
01:06:42,372 --> 01:06:45,792
Why, sure. Hey, why don't you kids
drive down with us, huh?

1263
01:06:46,126 --> 01:06:48,921
Oh, I'm afraid
I couldn't get away, Sam.

1264
01:06:49,004 --> 01:06:51,048
Still got the nose
to the old grindstone, eh?

1265
01:06:51,131 --> 01:06:54,718
Jane, I offered to let George in
on the ground floor in plastics,

1266
01:06:54,801 --> 01:06:56,011
and he turned me down cold.

1267
01:06:56,094 --> 01:06:58,889
- Oh, now, don't rub it in.
- I'm not rubbing it in.

1268
01:06:58,972 --> 01:07:00,557
Well, I guess we better run along.

1269
01:07:00,641 --> 01:07:02,726
- Awfully happy to have met you, Mary.
- Nice meeting you, too.

1270
01:07:02,809 --> 01:07:04,186
- Goodbye. Glad to see you.
- Goodbye, George.

1271
01:07:04,269 --> 01:07:05,729
So long, George.
See you in the funny papers.

1272
01:07:05,812 --> 01:07:07,898
- So long, Mary.
- Bye, Sam. Have fun.

1273
01:07:07,981 --> 01:07:09,983
- Thanks for dropping around.
- Florida!

1274
01:07:10,067 --> 01:07:11,777
- Hee-haw!
- Hee-haw.

1275
01:07:41,056 --> 01:07:42,349
Thank you, sir.

1276
01:07:42,933 --> 01:07:44,935
- That's quite a cigar, Mr. Potter.
- You like it?

1277
01:07:45,018 --> 01:07:46,562
I'll send you a box.

1278
01:07:55,404 --> 01:07:56,697
Well, I...

1279
01:07:58,240 --> 01:07:59,741
I suppose
I'll find out sooner or later,

1280
01:07:59,825 --> 01:08:02,703
but just what exactly
did you want to see me about?

1281
01:08:04,788 --> 01:08:08,375
George, now that's just what I like
SO much about you.

1282
01:08:08,875 --> 01:08:12,546
George, I am an old man,
and most people hate me.

1283
01:08:12,629 --> 01:08:15,632
But I don't like them, either,
so that makes it all even.

1284
01:08:15,716 --> 01:08:17,884
You know just as well as I do

1285
01:08:17,968 --> 01:08:20,470
that I run practically everything
in this town

1286
01:08:20,554 --> 01:08:23,181
but the Bailey Building and Loan.

1287
01:08:23,640 --> 01:08:25,726
You know, also,
that for a number of years

1288
01:08:25,809 --> 01:08:27,728
I've been trying to get control of it.

1289
01:08:27,811 --> 01:08:30,439
Or kill it.
But I haven't been able to do it.

1290
01:08:30,647 --> 01:08:32,608
You have been stopping me.

1291
01:08:33,734 --> 01:08:36,862
In fact, you have beaten me, George,

1292
01:08:36,945 --> 01:08:41,408
and as anyone in this county
can tell you, that takes some doing.

1293
01:08:42,534 --> 01:08:45,245
Take during the Depression,
for instance.

1294
01:08:45,329 --> 01:08:48,415
You and I were the only ones
that kept our heads.

1295
01:08:48,498 --> 01:08:52,461
You saved the Building and Loan.
I saved all the rest.

1296
01:08:52,544 --> 01:08:55,172
Yes. Well, most people say
you stole all the rest.

1297
01:08:55,255 --> 01:08:58,592
The envious ones say that,
George, the suckers.

1298
01:08:59,551 --> 01:09:03,597
Now, I have stated
my side very frankly.

1299
01:09:03,972 --> 01:09:06,099
Now let's look at your side.

1300
01:09:07,059 --> 01:09:13,940
Young man, 27-28, married,
making, say, $40 a week.

1301
01:09:14,107 --> 01:09:16,026
- $45.
- $45.

1302
01:09:16,109 --> 01:09:17,235
$45.

1303
01:09:17,611 --> 01:09:21,490
Out of which, after supporting
your mother and paying your bills,

1304
01:09:21,573 --> 01:09:24,660
you're able to keep, say, $10,
if you skimp.

1305
01:09:24,785 --> 01:09:29,081
A child or two comes along, and you
won't even be able to save the $10.

1306
01:09:29,164 --> 01:09:34,711
Now, if this young man of 28
was a common, ordinary yokel,

1307
01:09:34,795 --> 01:09:36,380
I'd say he was doing fine.

1308
01:09:36,463 --> 01:09:40,717
But George Bailey is not a common,
ordinary yokel.

1309
01:09:40,801 --> 01:09:44,513
He is an intelligent, smart,
ambitious young man,

1310
01:09:44,596 --> 01:09:47,808
who hates his job,
who hates the Building and Loan

1311
01:09:47,891 --> 01:09:49,309
almost as much as I do.

1312
01:09:50,268 --> 01:09:54,856
A young man who's been dying to get
out on his own ever since he was born.

1313
01:09:55,273 --> 01:09:58,068
A young man... The smartest one
of the crowd, mind you.

1314
01:09:58,151 --> 01:09:59,778
A young man who has to sit by

1315
01:09:59,861 --> 01:10:03,323
and watch his friends go places
because he's trapped.

1316
01:10:03,407 --> 01:10:07,077
Yes, sir,
trapped into frittering his life away,

1317
01:10:07,160 --> 01:10:09,746
playing nursemaid
to a lot of garlic eaters.

1318
01:10:11,206 --> 01:10:14,501
Do I paint a correct picture,
or do I exaggerate?

1319
01:10:17,003 --> 01:10:19,548
- Now, what's your point, Mr. Potter?
- My point?

1320
01:10:19,631 --> 01:10:22,217
- My point is I want to hire you.
- Hire me?

1321
01:10:22,300 --> 01:10:25,554
Yeah, I want you to manage my affairs,
run my properties.

1322
01:10:25,804 --> 01:10:30,892
George, I'll start you out
at $20,000 a year.

1323
01:10:34,730 --> 01:10:37,691
$20,000 a year?

1324
01:10:37,774 --> 01:10:41,153
You wouldn't mind living
in the nicest house in town,

1325
01:10:41,236 --> 01:10:43,947
buying your wife
a lot of fine clothes,

1326
01:10:44,030 --> 01:10:46,783
a couple of business trips
to New York a year,

1327
01:10:46,867 --> 01:10:48,744
maybe once in a while Europe.

1328
01:10:48,827 --> 01:10:50,120
You wouldn't mind that,
would you, George?

1329
01:10:50,203 --> 01:10:51,580
Would 1?

1330
01:10:54,583 --> 01:10:56,918
You're not talking to somebody else
around here, are you?

1331
01:10:57,002 --> 01:10:58,712
You know, this is me.
You remember me?

1332
01:10:58,795 --> 01:11:00,589
- George Bailey.
- George Bailey.

1333
01:11:00,672 --> 01:11:03,717
Yeah, George Bailey,
whose ship has just come in.

1334
01:11:05,051 --> 01:11:08,263
Provided he has enough brains
to climb aboard.

1335
01:11:16,563 --> 01:11:18,023
Holy mackerel.

1336
01:11:21,067 --> 01:11:23,653
Well, how about the Building and Loan?

1337
01:11:23,737 --> 01:11:27,157
Oh, confound it, man,
are you afraid of success?

1338
01:11:27,240 --> 01:11:29,785
I'm offering you
a three-years contract

1339
01:11:29,868 --> 01:11:32,162
at $20,000 a year, starting today.

1340
01:11:32,245 --> 01:11:33,997
Is it a deal, or isn't it?

1341
01:11:35,624 --> 01:11:37,292
Well, Mr. Potter, I...

1342
01:11:37,501 --> 01:11:41,296
I know I ought to jump
at the chance but I... I just...

1343
01:11:42,422 --> 01:11:44,591
I wonder if it would be possible

1344
01:11:44,674 --> 01:11:46,468
for you to give me 24 hours
to think it over?

1345
01:11:46,551 --> 01:11:48,220
Sure, sure, sure.

1346
01:11:48,303 --> 01:11:50,847
You go on home
and talk about it to your wife.

1347
01:11:50,931 --> 01:11:52,516
I'd like to do that.

1348
01:11:52,599 --> 01:11:54,935
Yeah. In the meantime,
I'll draw up the papers.

1349
01:11:55,018 --> 01:11:56,937
- All right, sir.
- Okay, George?

1350
01:11:58,438 --> 01:11:59,940
Okay, Mr. Potter.

1351
01:12:08,114 --> 01:12:12,452
No. No. No, no,
now wait a minute, here.

1352
01:12:13,286 --> 01:12:16,164
I don't need 24 hours.
I don't have to talk to anybody.

1353
01:12:16,248 --> 01:12:17,916
I know right now,
and the answer is no.

1354
01:12:17,999 --> 01:12:19,835
No, doggone it!

1355
01:12:19,918 --> 01:12:22,546
You sit around here,
and you spin your little webs,

1356
01:12:22,629 --> 01:12:25,090
and you think the whole world
revolves around you and your money.

1357
01:12:25,173 --> 01:12:26,716
Well, it doesn't, Mr. Potter.

1358
01:12:26,800 --> 01:12:30,011
In the whole vast
configuration of things,

1359
01:12:30,095 --> 01:12:32,889
I'd say you were nothing
but a scurvy little spider.

1360
01:12:32,973 --> 01:12:33,974
You...

1361
