1447
01:17:35,066 --> 01:17:36,568
Extra! Read all about it!

1448
01:17:36,651 --> 01:17:39,112
George, George! It's Harry now
on long-distance from Washington.

1449
01:17:39,195 --> 01:17:40,697
Harry! What do you know about that!

1450
01:17:40,780 --> 01:17:42,323
He reversed the charges.
It's okay, isn't it?

1451
01:17:42,407 --> 01:17:44,701
Reversed the charges?
Of course it is for a hero.

1452
01:17:44,784 --> 01:17:45,910
Harry!

1453
01:17:45,994 --> 01:17:50,331
You old seven times
a son of a gun. Congratulations.

1454
01:17:50,498 --> 01:17:53,001
How's Mother standing it? She did?

1455
01:17:53,334 --> 01:17:54,586
What do you know?

1456
01:17:54,669 --> 01:17:56,379
Mother had lunch
with the President's wife.

1457
01:17:56,462 --> 01:17:57,547
Wait till Martha hears about this.

1458
01:17:57,630 --> 01:17:59,757
- What did they have to eat?
- What'd they have to eat?

1459
01:17:59,841 --> 01:18:00,884
Harry,

1460
01:18:00,967 --> 01:18:04,053
you should see what they're cooking up
in the town for you.

1461
01:18:04,137 --> 01:18:05,221
Oh, they are?

1462
01:18:05,305 --> 01:18:07,223
The Navy's gonna fly Mother home
this afternoon.

1463
01:18:07,307 --> 01:18:08,433
In a plane?

1464
01:18:08,808 --> 01:18:10,935
What? Uncle Billy?

1465
01:18:11,019 --> 01:18:13,396
- Has Uncle Billy come in yet?
- He stopped at the bank first.

1466
01:18:13,479 --> 01:18:16,900
He's not here right now, Harry.
But look, now, tell me about it.

1467
01:18:16,983 --> 01:18:18,067
- George. George, George.
- What?

1468
01:18:18,151 --> 01:18:19,235
- That man is here again.
- What man?

1469
01:18:19,319 --> 01:18:20,945
Bank examiner.

1470
01:18:21,988 --> 01:18:24,157
Harry, talk to Eustace for a minute,
will you?

1471
01:18:24,240 --> 01:18:25,408
I'll be right back.

1472
01:18:25,491 --> 01:18:26,993
- Well...
- Harry.

1473
01:18:27,076 --> 01:18:29,579
- Good morning, sir.
- Carter, bank examiner.

1474
01:18:29,662 --> 01:18:31,789
- Mr. Carter, Merry Christmas.
- Merry Christmas.

1475
01:18:31,873 --> 01:18:33,625
We're all excited around here.

1476
01:18:33,708 --> 01:18:35,752
My brother just got
the Congressional Medal of Honor.

1477
01:18:35,835 --> 01:18:38,630
- The President just decorated him.
- Well, I guess they do those things.

1478
01:18:38,713 --> 01:18:41,549
- Well, I trust you had a good year.
- Good year?

1479
01:18:41,758 --> 01:18:44,844
Well, between you and me,
Mr. Carter, we're broke.

1480
01:18:45,094 --> 01:18:46,763
Yeah, very funny.

1481
01:18:48,932 --> 01:18:51,726
Well, now,
come right in here, Mr. Carter.

1482
01:18:51,809 --> 01:18:54,062
Although I shouldn't wonder
when you okay reverse charges

1483
01:18:54,145 --> 01:18:55,897
on personal long-distance calls.

1484
01:18:55,980 --> 01:18:57,565
- George, shall we hang up?
- No, no.

1485
01:18:57,649 --> 01:18:59,275
He wants to talk to Uncle Billy.
You just hold on, there.

1486
01:18:59,359 --> 01:19:02,153
Now, if you'll cooperate, I'd like to
finish with you by tonight.

1487
01:19:02,237 --> 01:19:05,114
I want to spend Christmas
in Elmira with my family.

1488
01:19:05,198 --> 01:19:06,449
I don't blame you at all, Mr. Carter.

1489
01:19:06,532 --> 01:19:07,825
Just step right in here.
We'll fix you up.

1490
01:19:08,868 --> 01:19:11,913
December 24.

1491
01:19:17,502 --> 01:19:20,088
$8,000.

1492
01:19:21,214 --> 01:19:23,800
- Merry Christmas, Mr. Potter.
- Merry Christmas.

1493
01:19:23,883 --> 01:19:27,303
Well, good morning, Mr. Potter.
What's the news?

1494
01:19:27,387 --> 01:19:30,890
Well, well, well, "Harry Bailey
wins Congressional Medal."

1495
01:19:30,974 --> 01:19:33,309
That couldn't be
one of the Bailey boys.

1496
01:19:33,393 --> 01:19:35,603
You just can't keep
those Baileys down,

1497
01:19:35,687 --> 01:19:36,980
now can you, Mr. Potter?

1498
01:19:37,063 --> 01:19:39,482
How does slacker George
feel about that?

1499
01:19:39,565 --> 01:19:40,817
Very jealous. Very jealous.

1500
01:19:40,900 --> 01:19:43,111
He only lost
three buttons off his vest.

1501
01:19:43,194 --> 01:19:45,238
Of course,
slacker George would've gotten

1502
01:19:45,321 --> 01:19:47,198
two of these medals if he had gone.

1503
01:19:47,282 --> 01:19:48,825
- Bad ear.
- Yes.

1504
01:19:48,992 --> 01:19:52,453
After all, Potter, some people
like George had to stay at home.

1505
01:19:52,537 --> 01:19:56,582
Not every heel was
in Germany and Japan.

1506
01:20:03,881 --> 01:20:07,593
- Good morning, Mr. Bailey.
- Good morning, Horace.

1507
01:20:08,636 --> 01:20:11,347
- I guess you forgot something.
- Huh?

1508
01:20:11,431 --> 01:20:13,308
- You forgot something.
- What?

1509
01:20:13,391 --> 01:20:14,892
Well, aren't you going
to make a deposit?

1510
01:20:14,976 --> 01:20:15,977
Oh, sure, sure I am.

1511
01:20:16,060 --> 01:20:19,439
Well, then, it's usually customary
to bring the money with you.

1512
01:20:20,023 --> 01:20:24,235
Oh, shucks, I knew I had.

1513
01:20:26,070 --> 01:20:28,156
How about that finger there?

1514
01:20:28,239 --> 01:20:29,324
Well, I...

1515
01:20:30,199 --> 01:20:31,409
Bailey.

1516
01:20:37,915 --> 01:20:40,293
Take me back there. Hurry up.

1517
01:20:42,420 --> 01:20:44,630
Come on, look sharp.

1518
01:21:02,315 --> 01:21:03,858
Take me back.

1519
01:21:13,659 --> 01:21:15,119
Just make yourself at home,
Mr. Carter.

1520
01:21:15,203 --> 01:21:17,038
I got those books for you here.

1521
01:21:17,121 --> 01:21:18,539
Oh, hello, Vi.

1522
01:21:18,623 --> 01:21:20,208
George, can I see you for a second?

1523
01:21:20,291 --> 01:21:23,169
Why, of course you can.
Go on in the office there.

1524
01:21:23,336 --> 01:21:26,172
Uncle Billy, talk to Harry.
He's on the telephone.

1525
01:21:26,964 --> 01:21:29,759
Hurry up, Uncle Billy, hurry.
Long distance, Washington.

1526
01:21:29,842 --> 01:21:30,927
Hey, here's Harry on the phone.

1527
01:21:31,010 --> 01:21:32,762
You know, your nephew,
remember? Harry.

1528
01:21:32,845 --> 01:21:34,138
- Here he is.
- Hurry up.

1529
01:21:34,639 --> 01:21:38,393
Hello? Hello.
Yes, Harry, yes, everything's fine.

1530
01:21:38,893 --> 01:21:41,104
I ought to have my head examined.

1531
01:21:41,187 --> 01:21:44,065
$8,000. It's got to be somewhere.

1532
01:21:50,238 --> 01:21:51,489
Here you are.

1533
01:21:52,031 --> 01:21:53,157
Character?

1534
01:21:53,783 --> 01:21:55,076
If I had any character, I'd...

1535
01:21:55,159 --> 01:21:57,036
It takes a lot of character
to leave your hometown

1536
01:21:57,120 --> 01:21:58,579
and start all over again.

1537
01:21:58,663 --> 01:22:00,123
No, George, don't.

1538
01:22:00,206 --> 01:22:02,250
Here now, you're broke, aren't you?

1539
01:22:02,333 --> 01:22:03,960
- I know, but...
- What do you want to do,

1540
01:22:04,043 --> 01:22:05,837
hock your furs and that hat?

1541
01:22:07,213 --> 01:22:08,673
You want to walk to New York?

1542
01:22:08,756 --> 01:22:10,550
You know, they charge
for meals and rent up there,

1543
01:22:10,633 --> 01:22:12,051
just the same as they do
in Bedford Falls.

1544
01:22:12,135 --> 01:22:13,928
- Yeah, sure.
- No, that's a loan, now.

1545
01:22:14,220 --> 01:22:16,514
That's my business, Building and Loan.

1546
01:22:16,681 --> 01:22:19,725
Besides, you'll get a job.
Good luck to you.

1547
01:22:19,809 --> 01:22:21,978
I'm glad I know you, George Bailey.

1548
01:22:27,191 --> 01:22:29,944
- Say hello to New York for me.
- Yeah, yeah, sure, I will.

1549
01:22:30,027 --> 01:22:31,904
Now, let's hear from you
once in a while.

1550
01:22:35,908 --> 01:22:39,203
- Merry Christmas, Vi.
- Merry Christmas, George.

1551
01:22:40,079 --> 01:22:42,582
- Mr. Bailey.
- Oh, Mr. Carter, I'm sorry.

1552
01:22:42,665 --> 01:22:44,167
I'll be right with you.
Uncle Billy in there?

1553
01:22:44,250 --> 01:22:45,751
Yeah, he's in his office.

1554
01:22:45,835 --> 01:22:48,045
What's going on?

1555
01:22:48,254 --> 01:22:50,256
The bank examiner's here.

1556
01:22:50,798 --> 01:22:51,799
He's here?

1557
01:22:51,883 --> 01:22:53,968
Yeah. He wants the accounts payable...

1558
01:22:54,093 --> 01:22:55,678
What's the matter with you?

1559
01:22:55,761 --> 01:22:57,180
Come here.

1560
01:23:17,408 --> 01:23:18,409
Eustace.

1561
01:23:18,493 --> 01:23:20,244
- Yeah?
- Come here a minute.

1562
01:23:21,954 --> 01:23:24,248
Did you see Uncle Billy
with any cash last night?

1563
01:23:24,332 --> 01:23:26,792
He had it on his desk counting it
before he closed up.

1564
01:23:27,960 --> 01:23:29,545
Now, look, did you buy anything?

1565
01:23:29,629 --> 01:23:31,964
- Nothing. Not even a stick of gum.
- All right, all right.

1566
01:23:32,048 --> 01:23:34,675
Now, we'll go over every step you took
since you left the house.

1567
01:23:34,759 --> 01:23:35,760
- Right. This way.
- Come on.

1568
01:23:45,686 --> 01:23:47,688
And did you put the envelope
in your pocket?

1569
01:23:47,772 --> 01:23:50,900
Yeah, maybe, maybe.

1570
01:23:50,983 --> 01:23:53,778
Maybe! I don't want any maybe.
We've got to find that money!

1571
01:23:53,861 --> 01:23:55,404
- I'm no good to you, George.
- Uncle Billy, look,

1572
01:23:55,488 --> 01:23:58,074
do you realize what's going
to happen if we don't find it?

1573
01:23:58,157 --> 01:23:59,200
Listen to me.

1574
01:23:59,283 --> 01:24:01,077
Do you have any secret hiding place
here in the house?

1575
01:24:01,160 --> 01:24:03,204
Some place you would have...
Some place you hide the money?

1576
01:24:03,287 --> 01:24:04,914
I've gone over the whole house,

1577
01:24:04,997 --> 01:24:08,918
even in rooms that have been locked
since I lost Laura.

1578
01:24:09,001 --> 01:24:12,088
Listen to me, listen to me!
Think, think!

1579
01:24:12,171 --> 01:24:16,300
I can't think anymore, George.
I can't think anymore. It hurts.

1580
01:24:16,384 --> 01:24:19,262
Where's that money,
you silly, stupid old fool?

1581
01:24:19,345 --> 01:24:22,098
Where's that money?
Do you realize what this means?

1582
01:24:22,181 --> 01:24:25,184
It means bankruptcy and scandal
and prison!

1583
01:24:26,352 --> 01:24:27,645
That's what it means.

1584
01:24:27,728 --> 01:24:30,982
One of us is going to jail.
Well, it's not going to be me.

1585
01:24:53,713 --> 01:24:54,839
Hello, darling.

1586
01:24:54,922 --> 01:24:56,716
- Hello, Daddy.
- Hello, Daddy.

1587
01:24:56,799 --> 01:24:58,634
How do you like it?

1588
01:24:58,718 --> 01:25:00,428
- Bless you!
- Bless you!

1589
01:25:02,179 --> 01:25:03,347
Did you bring the wreath?

1590
01:25:03,431 --> 01:25:05,266
Yes, Daddy, did you bring
the Christmas wreath?

1591
01:25:05,349 --> 01:25:06,350
What wreath?

1592
01:25:06,434 --> 01:25:08,894
The Merry Christmas wreath
for the window.

1593
01:25:08,978 --> 01:25:10,313
No. I left it at the office.

1594
01:25:10,396 --> 01:25:12,356
- Is it snowing?
- Yeah, it just started.

1595
01:25:12,440 --> 01:25:15,526
- Where's your coat and hat?
- Left them at the office.

1596
01:25:15,693 --> 01:25:16,777
What's the matter?

1597
01:25:16,861 --> 01:25:19,405
Nothing's the matter.
Everything's all right.

1598
01:25:27,079 --> 01:25:30,416
Come on, Pete, you're a big boy.
You can help me get this star up.

1599
01:25:30,499 --> 01:25:33,502
Way up at the top. There. That's it.

1600
01:25:34,086 --> 01:25:37,923
All right, fill in that little
bare spot right there. Right there.

1601
01:25:40,134 --> 01:25:43,638
Isn't it wonderful about Harry?
We're famous, George.

1602
01:25:43,721 --> 01:25:47,475
Bet I had 50 calls today
about the parade, the banquet.

1603
01:25:47,600 --> 01:25:49,727
Your mother's so excited. She...

1604
01:26:10,331 --> 01:26:12,833
Must she keep playing that?

1605
01:26:12,917 --> 01:26:15,711
I have to practice it
for the party tonight, Daddy.

1606
01:26:15,795 --> 01:26:17,213
Mama said
we could stay up till midnight

1607
01:26:17,296 --> 01:26:18,881
and sing Christmas carols.

1608
01:26:18,964 --> 01:26:20,466
Can you sing, Daddy?

1609
01:26:20,883 --> 01:26:22,468
Better hurry and shave.

1610
01:26:22,551 --> 01:26:25,513
- The families will be here soon.
- Families.

1611
01:26:25,596 --> 01:26:28,057
I don't want the families over here.

1612
01:26:29,809 --> 01:26:32,895
Come on out in the kitchen with me
while I finish dinner.

1613
01:26:32,978 --> 01:26:36,065
Excuse me. Excuse me.

1614
01:26:36,148 --> 01:26:38,317
- Have a hectic day?
- Oh, yeah.

1615
01:26:38,401 --> 01:26:41,320
Another big red-letter day
for the Baileys.

1616
01:26:41,779 --> 01:26:44,615
Daddy, the Browns next door
have a new car. You should see it.

1617
01:26:44,699 --> 01:26:46,909
Well, what's the matter with our car?
Isn't it good enough for you?

1618
01:26:46,992 --> 01:26:48,119
Yes, Daddy.

1619
01:26:48,327 --> 01:26:50,788
Excuse me. Excuse me.

1620
01:26:50,871 --> 01:26:53,124
- Excuse you for what?
- I burped.

1621
01:26:54,208 --> 01:26:55,584
All right, darling, you're excused.

1622
01:26:55,668 --> 01:26:58,462
Now, go on upstairs
and see if little Zulu wants anything.

1623
01:26:59,004 --> 01:27:01,090
Zulu? What's the matter with Zulu?

1624
01:27:01,173 --> 01:27:03,300
Oh, she's just got a cold.
She's in bed.

1625
01:27:03,384 --> 01:27:04,844
Caught it coming home from school.

1626
01:27:04,927 --> 01:27:07,471
They gave her a flower for a prize,
and she didn't want to crush it,

1627
01:27:07,555 --> 01:27:08,764
so she didn't button up her coat.

1628
01:27:08,848 --> 01:27:11,058
- What is it, a sore throat or what?
- It's just a cold.

1629
01:27:11,142 --> 01:27:12,435
- The doctor says it's nothing serious.
- The doctor?

1630
01:27:12,518 --> 01:27:14,270
- Was the doctor here?
- Yes, I called him right away.

1631
01:27:14,353 --> 01:27:15,354
He says it's nothing to worry about.

1632
01:27:15,438 --> 01:27:16,439
Is she running a temperature?
What is it?

1633
01:27:16,522 --> 01:27:19,108
Just a teensy one, 99.6.
She'll be all right.

1634
01:27:19,191 --> 01:27:20,693
Of course, it's this old house.

1635
01:27:20,776 --> 01:27:22,987
I don't know why
we don't all have pneumonia.

1636
01:27:23,070 --> 01:27:27,366
Drafty old barn. Might as well
be living in a refrigerator.

1637
01:27:27,616 --> 01:27:29,368
Why did we have
to live here in the first place

1638
01:27:29,452 --> 01:27:32,580
and stay around this measly,
crummy old town?

1639
01:27:33,372 --> 01:27:35,958
- George, what's wrong?
- Wrong! Everything's wrong.

1640
01:27:36,041 --> 01:27:39,295
You call this a happy family?
Why do we have to have all these kids?

1641
01:27:39,378 --> 01:27:43,090
- Dad, how do you spell "frankincense"?
- I don't know. Ask your mother.

1642
01:27:43,174 --> 01:27:44,925
- Where're you going?
- I'm going up to see Zulu.

1643
01:27:45,009 --> 01:27:47,386
He told me to write
a play for tomorrow.

1644
01:27:58,230 --> 01:28:02,026
F-r-a-n-k-i-n...

1645
01:28:02,234 --> 01:28:03,569
Hi, Daddy!

1646
01:28:04,737 --> 01:28:07,907
- Well, what happened to you?
- I won a flower.

1647
01:28:08,240 --> 01:28:10,075
Wait now.
Where do you think you're going?

1648
01:28:10,159 --> 01:28:11,827
I want to give my flower a drink.

1649
01:28:11,911 --> 01:28:14,121
All right, all right.
Now, give Daddy the flower.

1650
01:28:14,205 --> 01:28:15,498
I'll give it a drink.

1651
01:28:15,581 --> 01:28:16,916
Now, here.

1652
01:28:18,417 --> 01:28:20,544
Look, Daddy!

1653
01:28:20,628 --> 01:28:22,046
Paste it!

1654
01:28:22,129 --> 01:28:24,673
Yeah, all right, all right.
Give it here.

1655
01:28:27,092 --> 01:28:29,678
Now, we'll paste this together here.

1656
01:28:32,890 --> 01:28:36,018
There. There it is. Good as new.

1657
01:28:36,101 --> 01:28:38,229
Now, give the flower a drink.

1658
01:28:38,312 --> 01:28:39,772
Now, will you do something for me?

1659
01:28:39,855 --> 01:28:42,608
- What?
- Will you try to get some sleep?

1660
01:28:42,775 --> 01:28:45,694
I'm not sleepy.
I want to look at my flower.

1661
01:28:45,778 --> 01:28:48,364
I know, I know,
but you just go to sleep

1662
01:28:48,447 --> 01:28:50,241
and then you can dream about it,

1663
01:28:50,533 --> 01:28:52,701
and it'll be a whole garden.

1664
01:28:52,785 --> 01:28:54,036
It will?

1665
01:29:02,461 --> 01:29:04,213
- Telephone!
- Telephone!

1666
01:29:04,296 --> 01:29:05,756
I'll get it.

1667
01:29:07,633 --> 01:29:08,843
Hello?

1668
01:29:09,760 --> 01:29:11,804
Yes, this is Mrs. Bailey.

1669
01:29:12,137 --> 01:29:15,057
Oh, thank you, Mrs. Welch.
I'm sure she'll be all right.

1670
01:29:15,140 --> 01:29:16,725
The doctor said
that she ought to be out of bed

1671
01:29:16,809 --> 01:29:18,060
in time to have her Christmas dinner.

1672
01:29:18,143 --> 01:29:19,687
- Is that Zuzu's teacher?
- Yes.

1673
01:29:19,770 --> 01:29:21,105
Let me speak to her.

1674
01:29:21,188 --> 01:29:23,649
Hello. Hello, Mrs. Welch?

1675
01:29:23,941 --> 01:29:26,485
This is George Bailey.
I'm Zuzu's father.

1676
01:29:26,569 --> 01:29:28,279
Say, what kind of a teacher
are you, anyway?

1677
01:29:28,362 --> 01:29:30,656
What do you mean sending her
home like that, half naked?

1678
01:29:30,739 --> 01:29:32,366
Do you realize she'll probably end up
with pneumonia on account of you?

1679
01:29:32,491 --> 01:29:33,492
George!

1680
01:29:33,576 --> 01:29:35,327
Is this the sort of thing
we pay taxes for

1681
01:29:35,411 --> 01:29:37,538
to have teachers like you?

1682
01:29:37,621 --> 01:29:38,998
Stupid, silly, careless people

1683
01:29:39,081 --> 01:29:40,875
who send our kids home
without any clothes on?

1684
01:29:40,958 --> 01:29:42,793
You know, maybe my kids
aren't the best-dressed kids.

1685
01:29:42,877 --> 01:29:44,587
And maybe they don't have
any decent clothes...

1686
01:29:44,670 --> 01:29:46,505
That stupid...

